<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Sociologist     07-04 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Sociologist,0342</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Laennec cq</NOTE>
<HEAD>Home of Noted Haitian Sociologist Sacked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Well-known Haitian sociologist
Laennec Hurbon reported that four men with Uzi submachine guns
sacked his home early Monday in a raid that he said was politically
motivated.
   Hurbon and his servant told The Associated Press that the
intruders, dressed entirely in black and wearing black caps, forced
Hurbon to open the gates of the house at 2 a.m. and threatened to
kill him if he resisted.
   They said the gunmen departed half an hour later with $1,300,
leaving the house in great disarray.
   Hurbon, 47, told the AP, ``What I find terrifying is that we are
dealing with persistent political banditry. They scattered my work
notes, and trampled on the books of my library. It is ominous for
the future of a country when civil liberties are violated. In this
case, an intellectual was singled out. What next?''
   The sociologist is on an official mission to study religious
movements in the Caribbean. Hurbon, research director in sociology
at the Center For Scientific Research in Paris, is the author of
standard works in French on voodoo and Haitian culture.
   The incident was the second recent instance of violence in the
Haitian capital following the military overthrow of President
Leslie Manigat's civilian government on June 19-20.
   Last Thursday night, the house of Appeals Court Judge Ely
Legagneur was the target of a drive-by shooting. Legagneur said in
an interview broadcast over radio Haiti-Inter on Monday that he was
``not involved in politics'' and believed the gunmen had mistaken
their target.
   Over the weekend, rumors spread across the capital that Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy, who led the coup which overthrew Manigat and then
declared himself president, had died of a heart attack.
   A Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the
AP Sunday that Namphy had been seen that afternoon on the edge of
his swimming pool.
   Namphy has a record of heart illness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
