<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrumpBoat     07-04 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trump Boat,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>His Ship's Come In: Trump Shows Off His Yacht</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald and Ivana Trump, proud new owners of an
opulent yacht, gave the press a pre-party peek at their nearly
300-foot ``jewel of the sea.''
   ``This is the ultimate in boats and I feel strongly that this
country should have it,'' Trump said with Fourth of July spirit
Monday.
   The Trump Princess, with its six decks, 210 telephones and crew
of 31, is ``the jewel of the sea,'' he said.
   The original owner, Saudi arms dealer Adnan Khashoggi, got into
financial trouble and borrowed a lot of money from the Sultan of
Brunei, with the yacht as collateral. When Khashoggi defaulted, the
sultan decided to sell it.
   Trump, who picked up the ship at the fire sale price of $30
million, also saved money by registering it outside the United
States under a flag of convenience.
   A Bahamian flag flies from the stern, but Trump noted that ``the
American flag is right on top.''
   But the Stars and Stripes was a notch below the Trump insignia
on the mast.
   As liveried servants made preparations for the Trumps' inaugural
party, a Fourth of July bash for 100 close friends, photographers
snapped pictures of the luxurious fittings.
   ``Everything that looks like gold, is gold,'' said yacht manager
Jonathan Beckett. ``Everything that looks like suede, is suede.''
   Heavy-set guards, distinguished by their black suits, Trump
insignia lapel pins and walkie talkies, made sure reporters and
photographers didn't sit on the silk, feather-stuffed couches or
lean on the creamy leather bar rails, or set equipment on the
gleaming marble tabletops. One reporter was ejected for lighting a
cigarette.
   The Trumps said they bought the boat, sight unseen, for fun.
   ``It's different from a building,'' Trump said. ``We're getting
tired of buildings.'' He said they would use the yacht for
business, pleasure and charity fund raisers.
   ``We're going to have a lot of fun with it,'' Mrs. Trump said.
``We're going to watch the fireworks and celebrate the Fourth of
July. It's what America is all about.''
   ``You can get used to it,'' she said, her eyes sweeping the onyx
vases stuffed with lilies and orchids.
   Apparently the lavish yacht, refitted for $10 million, does take
some getting used to.
   Beckett said the first night he spent aboard as he brushed his
teeth, ``I looked down into that gold-plated basin and thought `I
can't possibly spit in that.' But that was two years ago. You learn
to live with it.''
   For nearly an hour, the Trumps obliged the press, giving tours
and answering questions.
   ``What does this tell you?'' Mrs. Trump was asked.
   ``Dreams can come true,'' she said.
   Her husband disagreed. ``It really tells her, you have to have a
smart husband,'' Trump said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
