<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Catholics 2ndLd-Writethru a0881 07-04 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Catholics, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0881,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Appeals To Traditionalists To Stay Loyal To Rome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to RESTORE time element. Picks up 3rd
graf, `On Thursday ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger said Mass in Latin at
Notre Dame Cathedral on Sunday and appealed to traditionalist
followers of rebel Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre to stay loyal to the
Roman Catholic Church.
   Lustiger, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Paris, performed the
traditional Mass as part of an effort to persuade Lefebvre's
followers not to join the renegade archbishop in breaking with the
Vatican.
   On Thursday in Econe, Switzerland, Lefebvre consecrated four
bishops in defiance of Pope John Paul II and was excommunicated.
   Lefebvre contends the Vatican has broken with true Catholicism,
by adopting Mass in languages other than Latin and in taking other
modernist steps since the 1960s.
   Lustiger announced Thursday that Mass would be said in Latin in
three churches in Paris each Sunday, as part of an effort to woo
followers of the French-born Lefebvre, who has many supporters here.
   In his sermon, delivered in French before thousands of tourists
and worshippers in Notre Dame, the famous Gothic cathedral in
central Paris, Lustiger called on the faithful to remain in ``the
sole house of God.''
   ``One cannot pretend to belong to the Catholic church while
cutting oneself off from the college of apostles,'' Lustiger said.
   ``Follow the word of love of God which is within you,'' he said.
``You should stay within the Catholic house.''
   At the church of St. Nicolas du Chardonnet nearby in the Latin
Quarter, occupied illegally by traditionalist followers of Lefebvre
since 1977, there was no indication that Lustiger's appeal would be
well-received.
   Outside the church Sunday hundreds of traditionalists crowded
around a stand where photographs of Lefebvre consecrating the four
bishops were selling for $8 each, the French news agency Agence
France-Presse reported.
   ``In truth, there has been neither excommunication, nor
schism,'' the agency quoted one unidentified worshipper at St.
Nicolas du Chardonnet as saying Sunday. ``All that is
disinformation by journalists.''
</TEXT>
