<DOCNO> AP880704-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Floods     07-04 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Floods,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floods in Sichuan Province Kills More Than 50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flood waters, fierce winds and hail storms have
plagued China's central Sichuan province in recent days, killing
more than 50 people and injuring at least 1,000, according to an
official report.
   The violent weather also ruined crops, disrupted transportation
and wrecked tens of thousands of homes, the China News Service said
in a report appearing today in Hong Kong newspapers.
   Gaoxian in southern Sichuan, more than 1,000 miles southwest of
Beijing, was hit June 25 with storms that triggered mountain
torrents and rock-mud flows that cut roads and communications, the
report said.
   The storm destroyed about 140,000 homes and 62,600 acres of
crops in more than 1,100 villages in Gaoxian, the report said,
quoting flood prevention authorities in Sichuan.
   Ya'an, about 80 miles southwest of the provincial capital of
Chengdu, was hit hard by storms Friday evening, the report said.
More than 16,000 acres of crops were destroyed and major roads were
blocked including the one linking Sichuan to Tibet, it said.
   The news service said more than 40 people died and at least
1,000 were injured in Gaoxian, but did not say where the other
fatalities occurred.
</TEXT>
