<DOCNO> AP880704-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Gulf-Aegis     07-04 0839</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Aegis,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even With Sophisticated Gear, Aircraft Identification Can Be
Difficult</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Attack Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Vincennes, which mistakenly shot down
an Iranian civilian jetliner, is stuffed full of electronic
wizardry that one admiral once called ``Star Wars at sea.''
   But the Pentagon says even with such sophisticated gear, it is
difficult for the ship's crew to identify approaching aircraft _
especially a head-on target _ from the radar blip.
   ``It has not solved all of our problems and it does not defy the
laws of physics,'' Adm. William Crowe, chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, said Sunday of the Aegis system of radars, computers and
weapons carried by the cruiser.
   The Pentagon has called Aegis ``the most capable
surface-launched missile systems the Navy has ever put to sea.''
   The system was designed to protect a naval task force, of about
10 vessels, from the increasing threat posed by the type of
anti-ship missiles which have already taken a heavy toll in the
Persian Gulf.
   The Aegis system uses ``phased array radar'' to simultaneously
track scores of planes and targets at ranges up to 2,000 miles and
destroy them up to 300 miles away. It can launch, track and target
up to 80 of the surface-to-air missiles it carries.
   Phased array radar emits a constant stream of radio signals and
uses computers to assemble a comprehensive and constant picture
from the electronic echo, unlike earlier radars, which rotated and
showed periodic blips that were much harder to track and analyze.
   Aboard the Vincennes, officers watch banks of video and computer
displays of the naval battlefield, and can fire Harpoon and
Standard anti-ship and anti-air missiles, heavier Tomahawk cruise
missiles, two 5-inch guns, and two Phalanx close-in, rapid-fire
guns for use against anti-ship missiles.
   Crowe, who briefed reporters after Sunday's shooting down of an
Iran Air jetliner, said the crew ``had about four minutes from the
time they picked up this target until it was declared hostile.''
   With the aircraft approaching at 450 knots, he said, time
presented ``a severe constraint'' in making an identification.
   ``One of the most difficult problems is from a radar blip,
particularly from a head-on target, to identify the type of
aircraft,'' Crowe said.
   The cruiser is equipped with gear to intercept and interpret
electronic emissions, such as radar or radio, identify the aircraft
or ships most likely to emit such signals, correlate that with data
from its own radar, and determine the likely identify of a target.
   Crowe told reporters that ``there were electronic indications on
Vincennes that led it to believe that the aircraft was an F-14,'' a
U.S.-made fighter that is the most lethal aircraft Iran owns.
   Crowe cited only ``electronic information which is classified
and I am not willing to discuss,'' but the indicators could have
included radio signals to or from the plane or nearby ground
stations, or emissions from the aircraft.
   U.S. warplanes, and many commercial aircraft travelling in war
zones, send out signals to prevent mistaken identity.
   Most aircraft also monitor standard military or civilian radio
frequencies. The Vincennes, said Crowe, warned the Iranian airplane
``on the civilian air distress net(work) three times in these few
minutes, and four times on the military air distress net.''
   ``We received no answers, nor did he vary course, nor did he
indicate in his conduct that he had received our communications,''
said Crowe.
   Following the attack by an Iraqi fighter against the USS Stark
in the gulf last year, said Crowe, the Navy adopted more aggressive
defensive tactics, and last September ``issued a Notice to Airmen,
NOTAM, which advised all aircraft in the Persian Gulf region that
U.S. Navy ships were taking additional precautions and of the need
to identify themselves and to state intentions.''
   ``Additionally, they were advised that failure to respond to
requests for identification ... or warnings, and operating in a
threatening manner could place the aircraft at risk by U.S.
defensive measures,'' Crowe told reporters.
   An independent observer, Capt. Richard Sharpe, editor of Jane's
Fighting Ships, said ``it is absolutely inevitable that mistakes in
classification are always going to be made.''
   ``If you remember the captain of the Stark, in exactly the
reciprocal case, was criticized heavily for failing to take
appropriate action early enough,'' said Sharpe in a telephone
interview from his home in Kingsley, England. ``Well, now here you
have a commanding officer who clearly has taken early action, and
will, of course, be criticized probably even more fiercely than was
the captain of the Stark.''
   The commander of U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf, Marine Corps
Gen. George B. Crist, told reporters last week he had stationed the
Vincennes at the mouth of the gulf to protect merchant shipping
against a battery of Iran's anti-ship Silkworm missiles. No
Silkworms were involved in the fighting on Sunday.
   The Vincennes has a speed in excess of 30 knots, is 563 feet
long, displaces 9,600 tons fully loaded, and can carry two
helicopters for reconnaissance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
