<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CityCelebration 1stLd-Writethru a0844 07-04 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Celebration, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0844,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beverly Hills Celebrates 75th Anniversary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with celebration; picks up 6th
graf, ``The town ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city of the rich and famous
held a cozy neighborhood bash Sunday, celebrating its 75th birthday
with an extravaganza rivaling those of the Olympics or the Super
Bowl.
   Jimmy Stewart, Scott Baio and Dinah Shore were among 1,000
singers, dancers and actors who offered a musical tribute, topped
by the unveiling of a diamond-encrusted slice of birthday cake
valued at $20 million.
   About 10,000 people watched the show at the Beverly Hills High
School football field. Donations from the event were to benefit 11
charities.
   Radio personality Casey Kasem led a 75-second countdown to the
show's start, which exploded in fireworks and the release of 1,000
balloons, including some shaped like silver-and-white birthday
candles.
   ``Happy Birthday, Beverly Hills,'' said Miss Shore, who emceed
the event. ``We have the best of everything here, the best schools
... the best hotels and the best restaurants. I'm glad I raised my
children here.''
   The 90-minute show featured skits, music and dancing
commemorating the city's historical highlights, such as the
turn-of-the-century discovery of oil.
   Desi Arnaz Jr. led 100 dancers and mariachi musicians in a nod
to the city's Mexican past.
   A dance tribute to the Beverly Hills Hotel featured Gene Barry
and Barbara Eden, who were joined by waiters, housekeepers and
other hotel employees.
   The sequence ended with a stream of celebrities, including
Stewart, Robert Stack and Dick Van Patten, who were escorted
onstage. Models decked in $20 million worth of jewelry portrayed
affluent hotel-goers, disembarking from $5 million worth of antique
cars on a 100-foot-long stage
   Motorcycle police, escorted by an armored car, drove onto the
stage for the presentation of a piece of birthday cake frosted with
2,600 white diamonds.
   ``Our birthday cake is so special you can only order it by the
slice,'' Miss Shore said.
   All the performers, including the University of Southern
Californa marching band, crowded onstage for a fireworks-laden
finale.
   Earlier, local chefs contributed a 1{-ton, 300-square-foot
birthday cake for this 5.6-square-mile city that has more tourists
than Disneyland, more doctors than most medical centers and more
money in its banks than any city except New York.
   The town was incorporated in 1914, two years after developer
Burton Green built a pink and green hotel on a lima bean field here.
   Ever since, Green's Beverly Hills Hotel has been the focal point
of the city's celebrity social life. Satirist Will Rogers was
inaugurated as the city's first honorary mayor there in 1923 and
many a mega-deal was consumated in its Polo Lounge.
   Among the other famous sights in the town is Pickfair, the
legendary home in the 1920s of Douglas Fairbanks and ``America's
Sweetheart,'' Mary Pickford, which has since been owned by Los
Angeles Lakers owner Jerry Buss and, most recently,
multimillionaire businessman Meshulam Riklis and his singer-wife,
Pia Zadora.
   The celebration is to climax Labor Day weekend 1989 when a grand
finale brings together the world's top fashion designers in what is
billed as the world's largest fashion show. More than 1,000 models
will promenade a 2{-block runway down Rodeo Drive.
</TEXT>
