<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PrisonCosts     07-04 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Costs,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Says New Prisons Cheaper Than Early Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says it is ultimately
cheaper to relieve overcrowding in penal facilities by building new
prisons and jails than by releasing repeat offenders.
   A report released Sunday by the department's National Institute
of Justice concluded that new crimes committed by released
prisoners cost society about $430,000 a year through such things as
police and court work, losses to victims and private security
expenses.
   But it costs about $25,000 for each prisoner each year to build
a new cell and maintain the inmate, the study said.
   ``Confinement is not too expensive when weighed against the
price of crimes that would otherwise be prevented by
incapacitation,'' said James K. Stewart, the institute's director.
   The report was based on a study of 2,190 inmates from
California, Texas and Michigan who were repeat offenders and given
early release. The study found those inmates committed an average
of 187 crimes a year.
   ``Public debate has mistakenly focused on the cost of
imprisonment compared with the cost of probation,'' said Stewart.
   The institute said sentencing 1,000 additional offenders to
prison annually would have required about $25 million a year but
would have averted 187,000 felonies that cost society a total of
$430 million.
   One-half the 2,190 prisoners said they had committed fewer than
15 crimes a year. Twenty-five percent said they committed more than
135 crimes and 10 percent said they committed more than 600.
   The study concluded that the $8.6 billion cost of operating the
nation's prisons and jails in 1983 was just one-tenth the over-all
cost of crime to society.
   The study said the bill for other criminal justice programs such
as police, courts and probation ran about $25 billion in 1983. Also
included in the total costs of crime to society were $35 billion in
victim losses and $31 billion spent on private security to avert
crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880704-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-04 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man and woman intent on getting out of
their clothes and into the Guinness Book of World Records stripped
down to their underwear 432 times in a store window.
   Delane Balliot, 22, and Newcomb Munt, 28, started their
record-book quest Wednesday and didn't quit until 72 hours later
Saturday. As long as nobody breaks their record, they hope the 1989
Guinness book will list them as the first record holders for
consecutive stripping.
   ``My feet are twice the size of my shoes right now,'' Balliot
said Saturday as she took off her high heels. ``I want to go home,
take a shower, go to sleep for days.''
   The professional strippers were allowed to rest five minutes
every hour during their bump-and-grind-a-thon, but often danced
several straight hours to accumulate time for catnaps, a spokesman
said.
   Both Balliot and Munt work as strippers for a singing telegram
company.
   For establishing the record, their employer is giving each of
them $500, a new set of clothes and a free trip to either New York
or Hawaii.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WOOSTER, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lot of bull was tossed around at the
Wayne County Fairgrounds. Even politicians stood in line to throw
it _ which came as a surprise to no one.
   And it only cost $1 a chip.
   The dried cow dung, the product of some of the area's finest
Holsteins, were used for a cow chip throwing contest Saturday, part
of a weekend Fourth of July celebration.
   Wayne County Commissioner Mark Altier, acknowledged as one of
the county's best ``bull throwers,'' tossed his chip 75 feet, 8
inches down the track in front of the grandstand.
   ``I haven't thrown a cow chip since high school,'' Altier said
with a grin. He said he had not practiced for the special contest
for politicians. ``I went in cold.''
   Other throwers followed the directions provided by organizers,
including: ``Place a plastic glove over one hand. ... Bring arm
back as if to throw a boomerang. Cow chips will not return on their
own accord. Release chip and let fly.''
   Colleen Bower, a candidate for Wayne County clerk of courts,
slung her chip 50 feet, 1 inch for second place among
femalecontestants.
   Mrs. Bower reached deep into the pile of dung to select her
chip, which she tossed overhand. ``There's nothing underhanded
about my toss. I'm a clean politician,'' she joked.
   First place among women went to Kathryn Buffington, principal of
Wooster's Boys Village, a school for troubled youths. Mrs.
Buffington's toss traveled 63 feet, 6 inches.
   ``I've been working out,'' she said. ``My job got me ready for
this contest.''
   County commissioner candidate Miles Priest managed a 56-foot,
4-inch toss. ``The only practice I've had is stepping into one on
my farm,'' he said.
</TEXT>
