</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maverick attorney Melvin Belli angrily
dismisses allegations by his wife that he beat her ``as absolutely
false.''
   ``I love women, I don't fight them,'' Belli said. ``I'm an
Italian. It's not our nature to beat up our wives.''
   Belli, commenting Sunday about his wife Lia's filing for legal
separation, said she has a reputation for making things up.
   ``It's a nasty, nasty thing,'' Belli, 80, said of the bitter
dispute. ``I think the people are sick of Lia Belli. I just want
out.''
   Mrs. Belli, 39, an unsuccessful state Senate candidate in 1984,
told reporters she wanted to end the marriage because her husband
was physically abusing her and falsely accused her of having
affairs with various celebrities.
   The famed ``King of Torts'' said he prefers to keep his private
life out of the press. But, he said, ``The only thing that I'm
really concerned about is this calumny that I beat her up. That's
absolutely false.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SITKA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author James A. Michener was greeted by a
brass band and community leaders as he returned to the southeast
Alaskan city where he wrote much of his latest novel, ``Alaska.''
   The 82-year-old novelist and his wife, Mari, arrived aboard a
cruise ship as they returned to the former capital of Russia's old
North American colony.
   The Micheners made their home in 1985 and 1987 in a log cabin on
the campus of Sheldon Jackson College.
   ``This is a very special place because we worked so long and
hard here,'' Michener said. ``We're delighted to see that log cabin
again.''
   The Micheners were to be grand marshals in the annual Sitka
Fourth of July parade today, and Sheldon Jackson College planned
``An Alaska Salute to James A. Michener'' with a fireworks display.
   The 19th century Presbyterian missionary for whom the college is
named is a major historical figure in ``Alaska.''
   ``Alaska,'' like many of Michener's novels, is a historical,
scientific story of Alaska beginning before mankind and including
events such as discovery by early Russian sailors, the 1867 sale to
the United States, gold rushes and construction of the Alaska
Highway.
