<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Vinson     07-04 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Vinson,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blues Musician Eddie `Cleanhead' Vinson Dead At 70</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blues singer and alto saxophone player Eddie
``Cleanhead'' Vinson, who got his nickname came from his baldness
and his reputation for his blend of instrumentals with vocals, has
died of a heart attack. He was 70.
   Vinson, who had been suffering cancer of the esophagus and
entered California Medical Center in mid-June for treatment, died
Saturday, hospital officials and family members said.
   He sang with the Cootie Williams Orchestra in the 1940s, and was
best known for such songs as ``Cherry Red,'' ``Kidney Stew Blues,''
and ``Somebody's Got To Go.''
   He often joked about his bald head and even referred to it in
the lyrics of some of his songs, including ``Cleanhead Blues.''
   The son of musicians, Vinson was born Dec. 18, 1917, in Houston,
Texas. He sang in local church quartets as a youth and learned to
play saxophone in high school.
   He toured the South and Midwest with bands fronted by Chester
Boone and Milton Larkin from the mid- to late 1930s, and in 1940
toured with blues great Bill Broonzy.
   Vinson moved to New York City in 1942, where he joined the
Cootie Williams Orchestra. He recorded ``Cherry Red'' during a
three-year stint with the former Duke Ellington sideman.
   Vinson ``established himself as a powerful blues singer with a
personal, broken-toned style,'' according to jazz critic Leonard
Feather.
   After a brief stint in the Army near the end of World War II,
Vinson formed his own 16-piece orchestra and appeared with the Ink
Spots during an RKO-Keith circuit tour across the United States and
Canada. He recorded his second hit, ``Kidney Stew Blues,'' with his
band.
   He returned to Houston in 1954 to teach music. He made
occasional local club engagements.
   Vinson moved to Los Angeles more than 20 years ago after being
rediscovered by band leader and promoter Johnny Otis. He revived
his career with club engagements in the United States and Europe
and new albums, including ``Kidney Stew is Fine,'' ``Cleanhead's
Back in Town'' and ``You Can't Make Love Alone.''
   Vinson regularly returned to perform at European summer jazz
festivals, and made a series of appearances with Count Basie.
   Vinson is survived by his wife, Bernice; three daughters; five
grandchildren; and one great-grandchild.
   A private funeral service was tentatively scheduled for Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
