<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Airbus     07-04 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airbus,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aircraft That Crashed In Gulf Is Consortium's Workhorse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Jet Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOULOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iran Air plane that the U.S. Navy
shot down in the Persian Gulf was one of 243 A300s built by Airbus
Industries and still in service with airlines worldwide, an Airbus
spokesman said.
   The wide-bodied A300 was the first aircraft put into service by
the European consortium in 1975 and is still the most widely used
Airbus plane.
   The Iran Air jet was an A300 B2 model delivered to the airline
in April 1982, said the manufacturer's director of communications,
Robert Alizart.
   It had recorded 11,448 hours in flight and 8,757 takeoffs and
landings, he said. The plane was one of six A300s Iran Air was
operating, all the B2 version.
   In different seating configurations, the A300's capacity can
range up to about 300 passengers. The A300 B2 has a range of about
2,500 miles.
   One of the newest Airbus aircraft, an Air France A320, crashed
June 26 while flying low over at an air show near Mulhouse in
eastern France, killing three people.
   The Airbus consortium is composed of companies from France, West
Germany, Britain and Spain.
</TEXT>
