<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-Shooting     07-04 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Shooting,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Official of Opposition Party Shot to Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official of the leftist National
Democratic Front coalition and parliamentary candidate in this
week's general election has been shot to death, law enforcement
officials said.
   Javier Ovando, the coalition's chief of electoral affairs and a
close associate of its presidential candidate, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,
was shot five times in the head late Saturday and found inside his
car at a downtown intersection, the attorney general's office said
Sunday.
   The coalition has mounted the strongest electoral challenge in
years to the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
Voting is Wednesday.
   The attorney general's office said the body of a person who has
not been identified was also found in Ovando's car.
   Police said they had no suspects and would not speculate on a
motive. They said an investigation was under way.
   Cardenas and other leaders of the coalition planned to meet with
Interior Ministry officials today to demand a full investigation.
   Ovando had dropped off a Front coalition official and was
driving to his Mexico City home before he was killed. Police
discovered 22- and 38-caliber cartridge shells inside the vehicle.
   Ovando served as chairman of the PRI in Michoacan state when
Cardenas, then a PRI member, was state governor.
   Cardenas led a dissident reform movement within the PRI last
year before he left the party to mount his own presidential
candidacy.
   Recent polls have shown Cardenas finishing second in Wednesday's
elections behind PRI candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   Since coming to power in 1929, the PRI has never lost a
presidential or gubernatorial race.
   Its members have often been accused by opponents of rigging
elections.
</TEXT>
