<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EvacuatingIran     07-04 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Evacuating Iran,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>400 Korean Workers To Leave Iran After Co-Workers Killed In Air
Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean contractor said today
it will stop building a gas refinery in Iran and evacuate all of
its 400 workers there after 12 workers were killed in an Iraqi air
raid.
   In addition to those killed, 45 Daelim Industrial Co. workers
were wounded Thursday in the Iraqi air raid on a gas refinery
construction site at Kangan, 560 miles south of Tehran.
   ``The evacuation is inevitable, because further trouble is
expected after the shooting down of an Iranian air jetliner by a
U.S. Navy ship,'' a Daelim official said on condition of anonymity.
   The official said Daelim workers, including the dead and
wounded, would be transported by two chartered Korean Air planes
later this week or early next week.
   Daelim, the official said, will stop building the gas refinery
until new arrangements have been made to ensure the safety of
workers on the site. The company was building the refinery under a
$180 million contract with Iran.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war for nearly 8 years and Iraq
frequently bombs industrial targets in Iran.
</TEXT>
