<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     07-04 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Gain Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar today rose to its highest level in more
than seven months against the Japanese yen in slow trading. Stock
prices gained slightly.
   On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange market, the dollar rose 0.35 yen
above Friday's close to end the day at 134.85 yen. It was the
highest closing rate since last Nov. 24. when the U.S. currency
ended the day at 134.93.
   The dollar opened at 135.15 yen and traded between 134.60 yen
and 135.20 yen.
   Volume totaled $7.472 billion today, compared with $9.8 billion
last Friday.
   An official of the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the dollar rose in early trading because of tension
in the Middle East, where the U.S. Navy shot down an Iranian
jetliner on Sunday, killing all 290 people aboard.
   But the dollar eased back, mainly on profit-taking and
anticipation of the Fourth of July holiday in the United States, he
said.
   The official said the dollar would be affected by the move of
future oil prices.
   Traders said Japan's central bank did not intervene on behalf of
the yen, but news reports over the weekend said the bank has plans
to stem the dollar's climb if the currency's rise quickens.
   On the Tokyo stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, the market's main barometer, fell a slight 2.13
points, or 0.077, percent from Saturday's half-day session to close
at 27,360.39 points.
   Volume in the first section totaled 900 million shares.
   One trader said that ``the trend continues from Saturday,'' and
added that the market was likely continue on its present course as
long as the dollar and interest rates continue rising.
   ``You're not going to get any real buying until you see
stability in currency and bond markets,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
