<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AirlinerAttack-Vincennes     07-04 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner Attack-Vincennes,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hoosier Town Shocked By Persian Gulf Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Attack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VINCENNES, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 290 civilians who died when the USS
Vincennes accidentally shot down an airliner over the Persian Gulf
may be remembered in a tribute by the Navy cruiser's namesake
organization, a member says.
   ``We know what it's like to lose lives in combat,'' William R.
Toth, the USS Vincennes Association's liason with the ship, said
Sunday.
   The association, comprised mostly of men who served on the two
ships of that name during World War II, is planning its 15th annual
reunion Aug. 8-14.
   ``There's no way of rectifying this kind of situation, so all we
can do is remember these people,'' Toth said. ``Our prayers and
those of the commuity are with the ship's commander and crew
members.''
   The current Vincennes is the fourth ship to bear the name of
this southwestern Indiana city.
   ``I think our citizens are shocked and saddened about what has
happened,'' said Mayor William D. Rose. ``When you hear `USS
Vincennes,' you think of Vincennes, Indiana.''
</TEXT>
