<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OrganizedCrime     07-04 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Organized Crime,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutions Viewed As Weakening Mob Ruling Body</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Commission'' set up by the most
powerful mob families to settle their disputes appears to be out of
commission, authorities say.
   The latest example of the ruling group's declining power came
last week when authorities handed down indictments that indicated
rivalry between the nation's two most powerful mob families had
escalated into a plot to kill reputed mob boss John Gotti.
   ``I think you can say with some degree of certainty there is a
bankruptcy of leadership,'' says Fred Martens, director of the
Pennsylvania Crime Commission.
   The ruling body that generally stabilized the five major Mafia
families _ Genovese, Gambino, Lucchese, Bonanno and Colombo _ for
more than a half-century was effectively dismantled by the 1986
Commission trial.
   Three reputed bosses were convicted. A fourth, reputed Gambino
head Paul Castellano, was shot to death on a New York City street
about the same time.
   Experts say a new wave of prosecutions has thrown the underworld
into further disarray.
   Last month, two indictments against reputed top Genovese leaders
were returned by a Newark federal grand jury. Closing arguments are
scheduled next week in Newark in the federal trial of 20 alleged
Lucchese family members and associates, and a powerful member of
the DeCavalcante family, which operates mainly in New Jersey, is to
go on trial in Camden in September.
   ``There are some more organized crime indictments coming,'' said
U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr.
   The Commission trial was a major source of disruption for
organized crime, experts say.
   With the Commission's end, the mob families lost a body to
settle disputes and handle business matters, said Ronald Goldstock,
director of the New York State Organized Crime Task Force.
   The alleged plan to kill Gotti, reputed head of the Gambino
crime family, and his brother Gene was contained in an indictment
aimed at reputed New Jersey figures in the Genovese family.
   The indictment returned Tuesday charges racketeering, loan
sharking, illegal gambling and a labor payoff scheme. Seven other
reputed Genovese operatives were named in a second indictment.
   Gambino efforts to move into northern New Jersey led to the
murder plot, which state police Superintendent Col. Clinton L.
Pagano said is a ``very dramatic sign'' the Commission is not
operating.
   When the Commission was functioning, the Gambino family might
have sought permission for expansion plans and the Genovese family
might have tried to settle differences through the group instead of
through killing, Pagano said.
   He said the tussle focuses on the northern New Jersey gambling,
loan sharking and labor racketeering operations once controlled by
Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo, whose operatives hold sway in the
Atlantic City and Philadelphia areas.
   Scarfo's grip has been loosened by recent prosecutions and the
northern turf now is up for grabs, Pagano said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
