<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT Friday's gold quote to $437, sted $436.40 as sent,
SUB 16th graf, `Gold opened ... ofr $437.15.' Picks up 17th graf,
`In Zurich ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly higher in quiet European
trading today, but below the highs reached in the Far East
following the U.S. Navy's downing of a civilian Iranian airplane in
the Persian Gulf.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   The dollar rose in Asia following news the U.S. Navy mistakenly
shot down the plane Sunday, killing 290 people. Investors often
rally behind the dollar in times of international tension.
   ``The dollar was bought in early trading because of the Middle
East situation,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial
bank in Tokyo.
   But European dealers said the dollar-buying eased in early
European trading which gets underway as Tokyo's business day ends.
   Trading was unusually quiet because American banks and
businesses are closed for the Fourth of July holiday, they said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 134.85 after
profit-taking. Later, in London, it was quoted at 134.93 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8245 West German marks, up from 1.8213
   _1.5180 Swiss francs, up from 1.5130
   _6.1460 French francs, up from 6.1375
   _2.0540 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0530
   _1,353.50 Italian lire, up from 1,352.50
   _1.2235 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2190
   The British pound continued to fall in London to its lowest
level against the dollar since last September. One pound cost
$1.6890 today, cheaper than late Friday's $1.7023.
   Gold opened in London at a bid $438.70 a troy ounce, compared
with late Friday's $437. At midmorning Monday, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $437.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $437.10, down from $437.50 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.24 to close at a bid $439.64.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.74 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Friday's $6.74.
</TEXT>
