<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0839EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WorldCup     07-04 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Cup,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Gets 1994 World Cup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will host the 1994
World Cup, soccer's world governing body announced today.
   The International Football Association, known as FIFA, picked
the United States ahead of Brazil and Morocco, the other two
nations that had bid to stage the 1994 tournament.
   The group's executive committee gave the United States 10 votes,
Morocco seven and Brazil two.
   Today's decision, taken in a Zurich hotel, also means that the
United States, as host nation, automatically qualifies for the
competition.
   The 1994 competition will be the 15th World Cup, which dates
back to 1930 and is held every four years. Since that time, the
tournament has passed between Europe and Latin America, soccer's
two traditional powerhouses.
   In 1990, Italy stages the competition for the second time.
   The U.S. proposal includes 18 possible stadiums throughout the
country, of which 12 would be used during the monthlong, 52-match
tournament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
