<DOCNO> AP880704-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Iran-Reaction 1stLd-Writethru a0429 07-04 0942</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Iran-Reaction, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expressions of Regret from Congress; Some Criticize Gulf Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with comment, picks up 2nd graf pvs,
``American military''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Airliner Attack Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress today generally defended
the U.S. missile attack on an Iranian passenger jet but they called
for a thorough investigation and a review of U.S. policy in the
Persian Gulf.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley, interviewed on NBC-TV's
``Today'' program, said all information about the destruction of
the jet should be released publicly ``to demonstrate that the
United States does not make war on innocents, that this was a
terrible accident, that we deeply regret it.''
   But the Washington Democrat said ``it would be a great mistake
for the United States to abruptly withdraw its forces after this
tragic accident.''
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., said the U.S. policy in the Persian
Gulf ``was never a very good one to begin with and this incident,
this sort of thing was very predictable.''
   ``If our policy remains the same, we'll see more of these things
happen,'' he said on CBS-TV's ``This Morning'' program. ``The
magnitude of this tragedy demands we take another look at this
policy.''
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., also interviewed on the CBS program,
said ``the policy of trying to protect commercial shipping in the
Gulf is absolutely right.''
   Other members of Congress defended the response of the commander
of the cruiser that fired the missle, but they also want answers
from the Reagan administration to some tough questions.
   ``American military forces must always have the right to defend
themselves, and preliminary information indicates that the on-scene
commander believed his forces were in imminent danger,'' said Sen.
Sam Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   But Nunn, D-Ga., said he wants answers to such key questions as
how the U.S. Navy has previously handled commercial airline traffic
in the region and what rules of engagement and decision-making led
to Sunday's decision to shoot down the plane. All 290 people aboard
Iran Air flight 655 were presumed dead after the jetliner was hit
by a U.S. missile and exploded in midair.
   President Reagan and other administration officials said the
crew of the cruiser USS Vincennes mistook the approaching jetliner
for an Iranian F-14 attack plane and fired in self-defense.
   Some members of Congress coupled expressions of regret with
criticism of the administration policies that put U.S. forces in
the gulf in the first place.
   Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the No. 3 man in the House
leadership, said, ``The Persian Gulf operation lacks definition and
reason, and this kind of tragedy is the inevitable result. If a
retaliatory act of terror is Iran's response, who will remember
this mission to protect commercial shipping or its purpose?''
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., a member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said that ``much of the responsibility rests
with the government of Iran for its irresponsible conduct during
these past years. But policy errors have led the United States to
become more involved in the Persian Gulf than our security needs
and the defense of freedom of the seas require.''
   But Republicans such as Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas defended
Reagan's policy of deploying U.S. forces in the gulf to provide
U.S. protection to neutral shipping.
   Gramm said he did not believe the incident showed any flaws in
U.S. olicy. ``We have saved lives,'' by being in the Persian Gulf,
he said.
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said that from what he knows so far,
``it seems reasonable to believe that the U.S. Navy acted in an
appropriate manner.''
   But he called the downing of the jetliner a ``horrible, horrible
tragedy'' and said, ``I, too, have many unanswered questions. I'll
reserve final judgment until I have more details.''
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., predicted the incident would cause
``major disruptions in the Arab world'' but said friction could be
reduced ``by having a body like the U.N. step forward and provide a
forum for some of the tensions that are going to be incurred.''
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, said Americans ``should give the Navy every
benefit of the doubt until all the facts are in with regard to what
was done to defend the lives of American sailors.''
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said the deaths were ``regrettable,
but the actions of the Iranian plane left the U.S. Navy no other
recourse.''
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., called the incident ``unfortunate,''
although he added, ``I don't think the captain had much of
alternative.''
   He said that even if the plane had been identified as an Airbus
jetliner, the U.S. ship's captain could have reasonably feared it
was a ``kamikaze plane'' since it ignored warnings and was outside
a normal commercial air channel.
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., said he was ``saddened that such a
tragedy should happen in a part of the world that already has known
too much human suffering.''
   One member of House Armed Services Committee, Rep. Buddy Darden,
D-Ga., said such a tragedy could have been foreseen because of
Iran's actions in the gulf.
   ``I'm not saying the Iranians deserved what they got ... but the
Iranians helped create the climate which led to the destruction of
this airliner,'' he said.
   Another member of the House committee, Rep. Dave McCurdy,
D-Okla., said the incident ``just has to weigh heavy on the captain
of the vessel, but also on the entire U.S. Navy.''
   ``But with any operation like that there is also going to be
some risk ... danger to U.S. forces or innocent bystanders,''
McCurdy continued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
