<DOCNO> AP880704-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 0912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     07-04 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wing South Africans Urge Retaliation For Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing politicians and a
pro-government newspaper today urged the government to retaliate
against African National Congress guerrillas for a bombing outside
a rugby stadium.
   ``The ANC should be killed at its origin, even if it is in
London or Lusaka (Zambia),'' said Moolman Mentz, a Parliament
member for the far-right Conservative Party.
   Two white men were killed and at least 35 people, most of them
white, were injured in Saturday's bombing, which occurred as
thousands of spectators were leaving Johannesburg's Ellis Park
after a rugby match.
   Twelve of the injured remained hospitalized today.
   The Citizen, a pro-government newspaper, said ``top South
African government sources'' were predicting retaliation for the
act.
   Police said the bomb, placed under a stolen car that had been
parked near the stadium since Friday night, contained 220 pounds of
explosives _ the largest ever detonated in Johannesburg.
   Sports administrators said they would tighten security at
stadiums.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu deplored the bombing and
offered to mediate between the government, the African National
Congress and another outlawed group, the Pan Africanist Congress.
   ``Until the authorities agree to sit down and negotiate real
power-sharing with the authentic leaders of our people, this
dreadful carnage will not end,'' Tutu said in a statement.
   There have been more than 90 bombings in South Africa since a
national state of emergency was declared in June 1986. Since
January, 27 explosions killed 12 people and injured 110.
   The African National Congress said recently it intended to step
up its military campaign. But the organization has declined
specific comment on recent attacks, including Saturday's bombing.
   The Sowetan, the country's only daily newspaper for blacks,
called the bombing ``distasteful and unwarranted,'' but indicated
doubt that the ANC was responsible for ``involving civilians in
violent attacks.''
   The paper blamed the bombing on the government's policy of
apartheid, which establishes a racially segregated society in which
the 5 million whites control national affairs, while denying a vote
to the 26 million blacks.
   ``We have always said that apartheid is institutionalized
violence,'' it said, referring to a government proposal last week
to tighten enforcement of residential segregation.
   The Citizen's editorial described the ANC as a terrorist
organization.
   Any steps taken against the ANC ``will have the support of the
great majority of people,'' it said.
</TEXT>
