<HEAD>Japan Air Lines Routed Farther Away From Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Jet Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan Air Lines said today its twice-weekly flight
from Tokyo to Athens, Greece, will change its Persian Gulf route to
avoid the zone where an Iranian airliner was shot down by the U.S.
Navy.
   A JAL official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
company's airliners will begin flying over Abu Dhabi, in the United
Arab Emirates instead of over Dubai, also in the same country but
closer to the gulf, where the Iranian airliner was shot down.
   On Sunday, a U.S. Navy ship in the gulf downed an Iranian civil
airliner with 290 people on board after mistaking it for a warplane.
   The airline official said a JAL DC-10 with 156 passengers and 16
crew members left Tokyo for Athens today using the new routing,
which is further south. He said the change added less than five
minutes to the flight time.
