<1ST_LINE>u i PM-FeudingPalestinians 1stLd-Writethru   07-04 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Feuding Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0497,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Refugee Camp Comes Under Heavy Shelling, 21 Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE casualties. Picks up 4th graf
pvs, Today's fighting ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat's guerrillas today held off
Syrian-backed PLO dissidents seeking to storm the Arafat loyalists'
last Beirut stronghold. Police said at least 21 people were killed
and 67 wounded.
   Six hours of fierce fighting, which included rocket barrages and
mortar fire, began at dawn in the Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camp.
   The latest casualties raised the toll to at least 148 killed and
594 wounded since battles broke out May 1 between Col. Saeed
Mousa's dissident Fatah-Uprising faction and Arafat's Fatah group.
   Today's fighting ended a week-long lull in the battle between
the rival factions for control of Beirut's two remaining
Palestinian refugee camps.
   Mousa's men overran the nearby Chatilla camp June 27 and had
been expected to move on Bourj el-Barajneh.
   Police said 20 rounds a minute were exploding today in the
sprawling shantytown on Beirut's southern outskirts and that the
fighting forced the closing of the airport highway that runs
parallel to the camp's western edge.
   Airport officials said flight schedules were not affected.
Travelers reached the airport by sidestreests.
   Black smoke billowed from Bourj el-Barajneh as Mousa's gunners,
deployed in Syrian-controlled hills overlooking Beirut, pounded the
camp with 120mm and 160mm mortars, rockets, and 106mm recoilless
guns, police reported.
   They said Arafat's loyalists responded with 62mm mortars.
   An official of Fatah, the main component of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, said by telephone that his men repulsed 10
attacks by dissidents trying to push into the camp today
   Fatah pushed Mousa's followers out of Bourj el-Barajneh and
Chatilla in earlier fighting.
   The dissidents then regrouped along the Syrian-controlled edges
of the camps and overran Chatilla last week in a 13-hour battle
that demolished the shantytown and displaced hundreds of refugees.
   The next day, Libyan mediators sponsored the evacuation of about
150 Arafat guerrillas from Chatilla to Fatah bases in the port city
of Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   The fall of Chatilla was a serious setback for Arafat and the
Fatah official said his fighters were determined to hold out and
defend Bourj el-Barajneh ``to the last man.''
   He said 80 percent of the camp was devastated by earlier
bombardments and that only 3,000 out of its original 20,000
residents remain.
   Dozens of civilians fled the camp during the week-long lull in
fighting after Chatilla fell.
   The camps have been largely destroyed by fighting that began
when the Israelis invaded Lebanon in 1982, besieged west Beirut and
hammered the shantytowns with air raids and shellfire for months.
   Pro-Israeli Christian militiamen massacred hundreds of civilians
in Chatilla and the neighboring Sabra camp in September 1982.
   And Syrian-backed Lebanese Shiite Moslems besieged the camps in
1985.
   They pounded them for more than two years in an abortive effort
to prevent Arafat from rebuilding the power base he lost when the
Israelis drove the PLO out of Beirut in 1982.
   The Shiites bulldozed Sabra flat, but Chatilla and Bourj
el-Barajneh held out until the Shiites lifted their siege earlier
this year.
   Mousa broke away from the PLO in 1983 in a Syrian-backed mutiny
by radicals opposed to Arafat's policies. Mousa set up his
headquarters in the Syrian capital of Damascus.
   The Beirut fighting has flared despite a reconciliation between
Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad last April to end a
5-year-old feud over control of the Palestinian movement.
</TEXT>
