<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     07-04 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Defends U.S. Action in Gulf But Expresses Regrets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today
expressed deep regrets about the downing of an Iranian civilian
aircraft but says the captain of the U.S. warship that fired on the
aircraft appeared to have made the right decision.
   Bush, speaking to reporters at the Detroit airport on his way to
an Independence Day parade here, said ``it appears the captain of
the ship followed the rules ... he did what he had to do.''
   The vice president, the certain Republican presidential nominee,
dismissed any comparison between Sunday's tragedy and the Soviet
destruction of a Korean airliner that strayed into Russian airspace
on a trip from New York to Seoul, South Korea, in 1983.
   ``I would just reject the comparison,'' Bush said. ``This plane
was warned. This plane was flying in a combat area. It's totally
separate, totally different.''
   Bush said he did not think the episode would jeopardize
President Reagan's Persian Gulf policies and said he believed that
Americans were pulling together in support of the captain of the
USS Vincennes.
   ``Obviously, as we celebrate our great national holiday, our
hearts go out to the loved ones and families of those who were
lost,'' Bush said.
   Asked how significant the disaster was in terms of U.S. policy
in the Persian Gulf, Bush said, ``I don't think its more
significant than other incidents but it is significant.''
   Asked whether his decision to campaign today might send the
wrong signals in view of the gravity of the situation, Bush said,
``This is a national holiday. It is appropriate that we celebrate
it ... there is nothing I could be doing about this matter in
Washington, D.C.''
   ``Life goes on and our mission goes on and the world keeps
turning,'' he said.
   Bush, who spent the weekend at his vacation home in
Kennebunkport, Maine, was to march in this Detroit suburb's morning
parade and then to participate in Fourth of July festivities in the
Chicago area and in St. Louis.
</TEXT>
