<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Gulf-Captain 1stLd-Writethru a0428 07-04 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Captain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Defends Vincennes Commander</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to edit</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the USS Vincennes said before
leaving for the Persian Gulf that he would defend his ship if
threatened, and the Pentagon is standing by his decision to shoot
down an approaching Iranian airliner.
   Capt. Will C. Rogers III received support Sunday from the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe, who said
the airliner was outside commercial air lanes and ignored repeated
warnings to pull away from U.S. ships in the gulf. He said the
airliner was mistaken for an Iranian F-14 attack plane and was shot
down with 290 people aboard.
   ``A full investigation will be conducted but it is our judgment
that based on the information currently available, the local
commanders had sufficient reasons to believe their units were in
jeopardy and they fired in self defense,'' Crowe said at a Pentagon
briefing.
   Rogers was born in Fort Worth, Texas, and now lists his home as
San Diego, the Vincennes' home port. Pentagon officials said they
did not have his date of birth.
   In a radio interview before the Vincennes departed for the
Persian Gulf in April, Rogers was asked what the ship's response
would be if attacked and said: ``If we are attacked or hostile
intent is demonstrated we will defend ourselves.''
   ``There is a very clear-cut set of engagement rules which we go
by and we're certainly not there to initiate hostilities,'' Rogers
said. ``We're there to defend ourselves and carry out what national
command authority dictates.''
   Crowe noted that those rules of engagement were changed after
the May 1987 attack on the USS Stark, in which 37 U.S. sailors
died. U.S. commanders in the region are under orders to act more
quickly and forcefully if their ships are threatened.
   Rep. Bill Lowery, R-Calif., said he toured the Vincennes during
exercises off the San Diego coast in February and found Rogers to
be ``a first-rate professional.''
   ``It's a well-trained and disciplined crew and skipper,'' Lowery
said.
   Rogers also was supported by a former Navy lieutenant who
survived the May 1987 attack on the USS Stark in which 37 U.S.
sailors died. Basil E. Moncrief Jr., who resigned from the Navy in
the wake of the attack, said Rogers had no choice but to defend his
ship.
   ``If the plane was unfortunate enough to be flying toward the
Vincennes while the Vincennes was engaging Iranian patrol boats ...
I'm not surprised this kind of thing would happen,'' he told the
Corpus Christi Caller-Times. ``I don't think the Vincennes had much
choice other than to fire.''
   Before taking command of the Vincennes, Rogers served in the
Pentagon as head of a section in the Planning Division of Chief of
Naval Operations, the commander of the Navy, according to a
biography released at the Pentagon.
   His first command was the destroyer USS Cushing, from September
1981 to August 1984, the statement said.
   He was commissioned in December 1965 through officer training
school and spent his first tour of duty aboard the aircraft carrier
USS Independence, qualifying as a main watch officer, a main
propulsion division officer and an assistant combat information
center officer.
   Rogers is married to Sharon Rogers, also from Fort Worth, Texas.
They and their son, Will Rogers IV, live in San Diego, Calif., a
main Navy base for the Pacific Ocean.
   The captain is not related to the late American humorist, Will
Rogers, according to the humorist's son, Will Rogers Jr.
</TEXT>
