<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Immigration     07-04 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Immigration,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President May Intervene to Keep Couple Together</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's personal interest may keep
immigration officials from breaking up a Chicago couple and sending
the wife back to Portugal, according to Sen. Alan Dixon.
   Dr. Margarida Magalhaes, a native of Portugal, came to this
country seven years ago to study medicine on the condition that she
would practice in her own country for at least two years.
   But in the meantime, she married a Chicago physician, Dr.
William Silverman.
   When the expiration of her visa became imminent, the couple
applied for a special waiver to allow her to remain in this
country. It was denied in March, when federal officials ruled their
separation did not pose an ``exceptional hardship.''
   ``I was devastated,'' said Silverman. ``My whole world fell
apart. I couldn't imagine that an American wouldn't be allowed to
live with his wife in this country.''
   This weekend, however, Reagan telephoned Dixon, a Democrat, and
asked what he could do to help. The senator had been writing
letters to federal agencies in the couple's behalf with little
success.
   ``With the president interested, it's a totally different
case,'' Dixon said Sunday. ``If he (Reagan) says that this lady's
going to stay in the country, you can bet on it.''
   The president is to discuss the case with members of his staff
Tuesday, Dixon said.
   Meanwhile, the Silvermans have accepted fellowships at Case
Western Reserve University in Cleveland, where they hope to be
together for two years of study.
   ``I'm holding my breath and hoping Mr. Reagan will do the right
thing,'' Silverman said. ``The 5th of July will be our Independence
Day.''
</TEXT>
