<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Libraries-NASA     07-04 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libraries-NASA,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UC Libraries To Drop Information Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least two University of California
libraries are canceling use of a computerized NASA information
service because non-citizens are banned from using it.
   The federal restriction, which applies to both classifed and
non-classified material, violates the UC anti-discrimination policy
and would be hard to enforce because of the number of foreign
students on campus, university officials told the Los Angeles Times.
   Also, librarians fear prosecution if they mistakenly give
research material to the wrong person.
   A recent letter by Calvin Moore, UC associate vice president for
academic affairs, urged libraries on all nine campuses to cancel
contracts with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
for the service.
   The database summarizes hundreds of thousands of scientific
documents on such topics as space flight, and tells where the
complete versions are located.
   UCLA and UC Berkeley libraries will sign up for a competing
service that is more expensive, the Times said.
   ``Of course, librarians are not interested in doing anything to
overthrow the government, but on the other hand they are very
interested in confidentiality and freedom of information,'' said
Nancy Koller, who works at UC Riverside and is president of the
Librarians Association of UC.
   The citizenship restriction has been in all contracts for at
least nine years and UC may simply have overlooked it, said John
Wilson, NASA's manager of the database.
   Wilson said that to his knowledge, no one has been prosecuted
for letting a foreigner use the service.
</TEXT>
