<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Oil     07-04 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Oil,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Little Affected By Iranian Jet Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Airliner, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices spurted briefly Monday and then settled
back down on news that the U.S. Navy shot down an Iranian civilian
jetliner in the Persian Gulf.
   The spot price of Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, jumped to $14.35 a barrel in Far Eastern
trading, up 20 cents from the close of trading in New York on
Friday.
   But later in London, the price had retreated to $14.15 a barrel.
   ``That's the usual knee-jerk reaction to anything happening in
the gulf,'' said Fergus MacLeod, an oil expert at the London
investment firm Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.
   An oil broker in the energy department at Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in London, who didn't want to be identified further, said,
``It didn't last. All it did was bring sellers into the markets.
Since then it has been sold down.''
   ``There was obviously a lot of interest from the U.S. to find
out what was happening,'' she said.
   MacLeod added: ``The basic perception is that unless that
incident changes the U.S. public opinion about having the fleet in
the gulf, then it won't have much impact.''
   The market is still weak because of oversupply and high stock
levels, the experts said.
   The broker said ``the underlying trend is bearish at the
moment.''
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is producing
about 19 million barrels a day, MacLeaod said. That is far above
the ceiling of 15.06 million barrels a day agreed to by 12 of
OPEC's 13 members in an effort to support prices at $18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
