<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Airport,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Vehicles Burned In Attack Near Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers believed to be opposed to the expansion
of New Tokyo International Airport set fire to 29 construction
trucks, police said Monday.
   No injuries were reported in the pre-dawn arson attacks, which
were triggered by devices with timing mechanisms, police said.
   In one of the attacks at Ichikawa, Chiba, about 20 miles west of
the airport, a 6{-ton truck and three other smaller trucks were
burned, said Kaichi Sato, spokesman of the Chiba Prefectural
Police. The vehicles were owned by a firm involved in the
construction at Narita Airport, about 40 miles northeast of Tokyo.
   In another attack, also in Chiba, three 10-ton trucks and a
smaller truck were destroyed in a parking lot, police said.
Twenty-one trucks were burned in the four other attacks, all in
Chiba, they added.
   The incidents followed two similar attacks in Chiba and Ibaraki
prefectures on Friday when 12 vehicles were destroyed.
   Kyodo News Service reported Monday that the Chukaku-ha, a
leftist radical group, claimed responsibility for Friday's attacks.
   Radical opponents and some farmers have engaged in sporadic
clashes with police over the years to protest Narita Airport and
more recently the construction of two new runways.
