<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChineseDolphins 1stLd-Writethru a0548 07-04 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chinese Dolphins, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0548,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flipper's Trainer Works To Save Endangered Chinese River Dolphins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS dateline to Miami. Coconut Grove is an area within
the city.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who trained dolphins for the television
series ``Flipper'' and tamed Orca the killer whale is going to
China to help save the rare Chinese river dolphin from extinction.
   The freshwater dolphins _ called ``baiji'' _ once flourished in
China's rivers and lakes, but pollution and river traffic have
reduced their numbers.
   Fewer than 300 are left in the Yangtze River.
   Ric O'Barry, 48, is leaving this month for a monthlong
fact-finding trip. He says getting the Chinese government to
understand what it will take to save the baiji from extinction may
be half the battle.
   The Chinese plan to build a semi-natural preserve by closing off
a loop of the river. Then O'Barry hopes to capture as many of the
dolphins as possible and move them to the preserve.
   ``They have to be taken to this place, settle down, fall in love
and start making babies,'' O'Barry said. ``We're talking about
re-populating the species, and that could take many years.''
   O'Barry said moving the dolphins could be as dangerous as
leaving them in the river, unless it's done right.
   Keeping dolphins calm during jolting moves in trucks or
helicopters is vital because they don't breathe automatically,
O'Barry said. ``Any time they want to end their life they simply
don't take the next breath.''
   Since marine mammal husbandry is practically an unknown field in
China, O'Barry also hopes to communicate his love for the playful
dolphins to the Chinese.
   ``They need to be as careful as they can and build a beautiful
spot for them to survive,'' he said. ``It's the same problem they
had with the panda. Until they got worldwide exposure, no one knew
about the problem.''
   O'Barry is borrowing $3,000 from his son's college fund to make
the trip, and is looking for a corporate sponsor for the baiji
project.
   ``The Chinese government is not putting much money into this,''
O'Barry said. ``Not that they don't care _ they're just overwhelmed
by human problems.''
   Chinese scientists have been studying several wounded baiji they
nursed back to health in a tank. But capturing and moving an entire
population was beyond their expertise and their budget, O'Barry
said. Dr. Xhou Kaiya, dean of Nanjing Normal University, contacted
him in hopes of leading a worldwide effort to save the species.
   As a trainer at Miami's Seaquarium in the 1960s, O'Barry taught
five dolphins to play the part of Flipper on TV. But to hear
O'Barry tell it, the dolphins were the ones training him.
   ``Dolphins are far more intelligent in our world than we are in
theirs,'' O'Barry said. ``It's taken about 25 years, but I can see
things from their point of view.''
   Through the Dolphin Project, O'Barry has spent years lobbying
marine animal shows and other organizations to release captive
dolphins into the wild. He admits that his solution to the baiji's
predicament _ isolating them in a manmade preserve _ is sadly
ironic.
   ``It's like the pandas,'' he said. ``The only ones to survive
will be born in captivity. It's either that or let them become
extinct.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
