<DOCNO> AP880704-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RazingHomes Bjt   07-04 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Razing Homes, Bjt,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Homes Fall To Wrecker's Ball In Connecticut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When talk show host Phil Donahue razed an
experimental, all-concrete house recently, the architect accused
him of betraying his nickname ``Mr. Sensitivity.'' But Donahue
isn't the only one swinging the wrecking ball these days on
Connecticut's ``Gold Coast.
   The rising value of land along this area of Long Island Sound 45
miles from New York City has encouraged property owners to tear
down older buildings, said Lucinda McWeeney, who is using a $25,000
federal grant to identify Westport's cultural resources, buildings
and sites.
   Within one recent two-week period, she said, the town of about
26,000 received applications for the demolition of six buildings,
four of which are historically or architecturally significant.
   ``We're finding people who aren't necessarily natives of
Westport but are interested in the economic value of property are
tearing down what we feel are significant structures,'' McWeeney
said. ``And it's not just in Westport. It's happening throughout
Fairfield County.''
   Donahue raised the hackles of preservationists last month when
he had the 26-year-old house torn down. Designed by internationally
known architect John M. Johansen, the house was described by some
as the town's most architecturally significant.
   Oak boards were used as forms in building the house, so that the
concrete walls had the texture of wood, including knots. The walls
were extended above the flat roof; some rooms were lined with
silken wall coverings.
   When he learned that the house had been razed, Johansen said,
``This wasn't a very exemplary act from a public figure. And
they've nicknamed him `Mr. Sensitivity.'''
   Donahue, who bought the house and 7.2 acres of land around it
for $6.8 million several months ago, said he wanted more space,
privacy and security for his wife, actress Marlo Thomas, and their
family.
   He said the house, which adjoined their property and had been
vacant for some time, had become a hostel for ``vagrants, lovers
and other strangers'' and denied that he wanted to improve the view
of Long Island Sound from his mansion. Donahue and Miss Thomas live
in a $3.5 million Tudor-style home on 3.1 acres overlooking the
sound.
   McWeeney said Westport, which is also home to actor Paul Newman
and his wife, actress Joanne Woodward, has changed drastically in
the last 20 years.
   ``It used to be a community of local artists and business men
who commuted to New York. Now it has turned into an office park,''
she said.
   ``Small local business can't afford to open here. They're
closing schools because young families can't afford to live here,''
McWeeney added.
   Her emphasis, she said, is on persuading developers to be
sensitive to local concerns about preservation before undertaking a
project.
   ``They have individual property owner rights, but we have visual
rights,'' she said.
   There are some protections for older buildings in Westport.
   The town, McWeeney said, has two local historic districts, which
means the exteriors of the buildings in those areas are protected
from change by state statute, and three districts on the National
Register of Historic Places. The historic districts include
18th-century and 19th-century residential buildings, some of which
are are now used for commercial purposes.
   In addition, Westport has a demolition delay ordinance, which
protects buildings older than 50 years and larger than 500 square
feet from immediate demolition. Those buildings can't be razed for
at least 90 days from the time of application.
   Will Tressler, a member of a citizens group in Easton, said that
town also is encountering development ``done without regard for the
character of the surroundings.''
   The Citizens for Easton organization, he said, is going to ask
the town of about 6,000 people about 8 miles northeast of Westport
to establish a design review board that would evaluate plans for
new development in terms of its effect on the character of the
surrounding area.
</TEXT>
