<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-SimoesPereira     07-04 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Simoes Pereira,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guinea-Bissau Planning Minister Killed in Car Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bartolomeu Simoes Pereira, the planning
minister of Guinea-Bissau who drew up a major economic
restructuring program for the West African nation, was killed
Monday in a car crash, according to a news report.
   Simoes Pereira, 40, was killed in a crash 17 miles north of the
capital, Bissau, as he returned from visiting his family, the
Portuguese news agency Lusa said in a report from the West African
country.
   Guinea-Bissau police and medical authorities made no statement
on the cause of the accident, but Lusa quoted unidentified
unofficial sources as saying it was believed a tire on his car blew
out and caused the accident.
   Simoes Pereira had been planning minister for the past four
years. He had drawn up a program backed by the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank to revive the poverty-stricken
country's economy.
</TEXT>
