<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Airliner-Reax Bjt   07-04 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Reax, Bjt,0889</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Governments Blame Iran-Iraq War for Downing of Jetliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES L. WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Monday the U.S. Navy was
``trigger-happy,'' but most governments appeared to view the
downing of an Iranian jetliner as the kind of tragedy made
inevitable by eight years of war between Iran and Iraq.
   Arab nations in the Persian Gulf renewed their call for an end
to the conflict that has turned the entire waterway into a war zone.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, U.N. secretary-general, said the
destruction of the jet Sunday by the U.S. guided missile cruiser
Vincennes ``appears to have been a tragic error.'' All 290 people
aboard were killed.
   He asked for ``the greatest restraint in these difficult moments
for the peace and security of the region.'' His statement was read
to reporters after Perez de Cuellar met in Geneva with Iranian
Ambassador Sirous Nasseri.
   Vatican radio called it an ``absurd tragedy'' in which innocent
people paid ``the price of a never-ending conflict that has already
sowed so much death and destruction. ... The possibility of tragic
errors, that add themselves to the destructive iniquities of war,
is particulary worrisome.''
   Gennady Gerasimov, spokesman for the Soviet Foreign Ministry,
said the incident ``shows American naval officers were not very
competent, or to use an American phrase, trigger-happy.''
   He said it proved American actions in the region were dangerous
and demanded: ``U.S. naval forces must immediately leave the waters
of the Persian Gulf.''
   According to the U.S. Defense Department, the Vincennes mistook
the Airbus for an Iranian F-14 fighter and the plane did not
respond to radio warnings.
   Another Soviet official said privately that the tragedy
strengthened the Soviet position that a U.N.-sponsored
international peacekeeping force should replace U.S. forces in the
gulf.
   Britain, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Belgium and the Soviet
Union have warships and mine clearance units in and near the gulf.
The United States has deployed more than two dozen vessels in the
largest national contingent.
   Citing the downing by Soviet fighters Sept. 1, 1983, of a South
Korean jetliner, in which all 269 people aboard were killed,
Gerasimov said the Korean plane was over a ``strategically
sensitive'' area of the Soviet Far East while the Iranian jet was
``flying only over its own territory and territorial waters.''
   The Soviet Union denounces Sunday's attack but will not follow
the ``bad example'' of ``wild'' American criticism after the event
in 1983, he said.
   Kuwait, which Iran accuses of being Iraq's ally in the war,
issued an ``urgent appeal'' for and end to the fighting and
predicted ``more painful incidents'' if it continues.
   Abu Dhabi's official newspaper Al-Ittihad Airbus passengers and
crew ``were the victims of the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war,'' and said
the disaster ``might be repeated.''
   Gulf News, an English language paper published in Dubai, the
plane's destination, called the incident the ``worst ever in the
region in recent times.''
   Dubai's other English-language daily, the Khaleej Times, said:
``Why the plane was permitted to take off when there was a naval
engagement in the area must remain a mystery and has yet to be
fully explained. How the Americans failed to distinguish between an
Airbus and an F-14 despite their sophisticated equipment is an
equal mystery.''
   The Vincennes had sunk two Iranian attack boats and damaged a
third just before the plane took off from Bandar Abbas, Iran, on
the short hop to Dubai.
   A Qatar daily, the Gulf Times, said continuing of the conflict
was ``senseless.''
   Bahrain's Akhbar al-Khaleej said editorially: ``If there is a
lesson to be gained from this tragedy, it is that the gulf war must
stop immediately.''
   Greece put the onus on the United States, but Washington's
allies in Europe generally used the occasion to call for an end to
the Iran-Iraq war, which began in September 1980.
   In Athens, government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said: ``This
tragic event ... is an international responsibility of the United
States. The parties involved must display above all calmness and
self-restraint. ... Only this way will it be posible to find the
real reasons for the airliner's downing and attribute
responsibilities.''
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany said on
a visit to Seoul, South Korea: ``This tragic event proves the
necessity of all efforts to contribute to peace in the region by
adhering to U.N. Security Council Resolution 598,'' which was
adopted unanimously a year ago and calls for a cease-fire in the
war.
   Britain has accepted the U.S. explanation of the event. Italy
said a special Cabinet meeting will be held Friday to discuss the
Persian Gulf situation.
   Switzerland, which handles U.S. diplomatic interests in Iran,
sent condolences to Tehran but would not say whether it had
forwarded a formal Iranian protest to Washington. Foreign Ministry
spokesman Michel Pache said Switzerland's policy of providing good
offices required discretion about its activities.
   Japan, which gets slightly more than half its oil from the
Persian Gulf, appealed for an early and peaceful end to the war.
   ``Our country ... considers it extremely regrettable that
valuable lives were lost and express our heartfelt condolences to
the victims and their bereaved family members,'' government
spokesman Keizo Obuchi said.
</TEXT>
