<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-Royals     07-04 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-Royals,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Queen Elizabeth, Prince Philip Arrive In Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Queen Elizabeth and
Prince Philip arrived Monday evening for a 41-hour visit marked by
some of the tightest security measures ever taken to protect
visiting dignitaries.
   The couple were welcomed at Ypenburg Air Force base near The
Hague by Dutch Queen Beatrix and her German-born husband Prince
Claus after the royal jet touched down.
   Elizabeth, wearing a gold-colored suit with dark broad-brimmed
hat, also was greeted by Princess Juliana, the former Dutch queen,
and her German-born husband, Prince Bernhard, as well as by Foreign
Minister Hans van den Broek.
   Also at the windy arrival ceremony was Princess Margriet, the
Dutch queen's sister, Margriet's husband, Pieter van Vollenhoven,
and Michael Jenkins, British ambassador to the Netherlands.
   After the greeting ceremony, Queen Elizabeth reviewed an honor
guard of the Dutch Military Police drawn up on the tarmac.
   Queen Elizabeth is in the Netherlands as part of the
tricentenary observance of the ``Glorious Revolution'' which
brought Dutch-born Prince William III to the British throne three
centuries ago.
   Her heavily guarded visit takes place against the backdrop of
two Irish Republican Army terrorist attacks in the eastern
Netherlands May 1 that killed three British airmen and wounded
three others.
   The incident has heightened security measures to an
unprecedented level.
   In addition, Dutch gay rights groups have called for
demonstrations during the queen's Tuesday visit to Amsterdam to
protest the recent parlimentary passage of Section 28 of the
British Local Government Act 1988.
   Section 28 bans the promotion of homosexuality in schools as a
valid family relationship. Protest organizers, who maintain the
British law discriminates against homosexuals, have called for
Amsterdam residents to show their opposition by hanging pink flags
from their windows during the queen's visit.
   Amsterdam is the venue of the only public event scheduled for
the couple, and police have refused to issue any public
demonstration permits during the visit.
   After the Monday welcoming ceremony the royal couple was driven
in a bullet-proof limousine from the military airfield to Huis ten
Bosch palace, the Dutch royal residence on the outskirts of The
Hague.
</TEXT>
