<1ST_LINE>r a BC-WimbledonNewspage 1stLd-Writethru a0575 07-04 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wimbledon Newspage, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Edberg Beats Becker in Rain-Delayed Wimbledon Final</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS second 1985 to 1986 in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WIMBLEDON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sweden's Stefan Edberg, relying on
precision volleys and court coverage, outdueled West Germany's
Boris Becker on Monday to win his first Wimbledon title in the
rain-plagued men's singles championship.
   Edberg, 22, defeated Becker, the 1985 and 1986 Wimbledon
champion, 4-6, 7-6 (7-2), 6-4, 6-2 on the famed grass Centre Court
at the All England Club.
   Edberg's big serves, solid volleys and control of the court
evoked images of compatriot Bjorn Borg as he earned the third Grand
Slam title of his career. He also prevented a West German sweep of
the tournament; Steffi Graff won the women's crown on Saturday.
   Edberg, ranked third in the world and two-time winner of the
Australian Open, beat Czech Miloslav Mecir in a spectacular
come-from-behind victory to advance to the finals. Becker, 20, beat
No. 1-ranked Ivan Lendl.
   The showdown, rained out Sunday after only 23 minutes of play,
took two hours, 52 minutes to complete on court. From scheduled
start to final point, however, it lasted more than 27 hours.
</TEXT>
