<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Perlman     07-04 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Perlman,0496</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT, Time set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Perlman Says Women See Beast As `Ultimate Fantasy Lover'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ron Perlman, who plays the beast Vincent on
television's ``Beauty and the Beast,'' says he has been amazed to
find himself a sex symbol because of the role.
   ``More than 95 percent of the people who write to me are
women,'' he said in an interview published in the July 9 issue of
TV Guide magazine. ``Their letters are filled with sexual
fantasies.''
   The 37-year-old actor whose half-man, half-beast character's
love affair with Catherine Chandler (Linda Hamilton) is
unconsummated in the show has received up to nine letters from one
viewer.
   ``Women say that Vincent is the ultimate fantasy lover, someone
who asks nothing in return but gives 110 percent,'' Perlman said.
``He evokes deep unconscious feelings of longing for a connection
to someone who understands things on a very emotional level.''
   Perlman said at first he didn't want the role, because he had
been hidden behind makeup in previous roles, including Salvatore,
the hunchback in ``The Name of the Rose,'' and a prehistoric man in
``Quest for Fire.''
   But Vincent, whose fangs and lion-like appearance belie his
soothing voice, is ``so romantic and heroic and poetic, it's like
playing Hamlet every week,'' Perlman said. ``This may just be the
greatest role of my life.''
   Perlman, who is married to fashion designer Opal Stone and has a
4-year-old daughter, Blake Amanda, studied acting at Lehman College
in New York City and the University of Minnesota. He performed in
plays by Shakespeare, Chekhov and Pinter with the Classic Stage
Company in New York and in 1976 was picked to star in a
two-character play, ``The Architect and the Emperor of Assyria,''
directed by Tom O'Horgan.
   His artistic success did not mean he was living well.
   ``I was one of these actors who landed wonderfully artistic
projects once a year and then just sat around because nobody ever
thought of me as a commercial property,'' Perlman said. ``I never
did soaps. I never did commercials. I tried, but I never did the
things actors do while they are waiting for the good stuff; I only
did the good stuff.''
   For Perlman, ``Quest for Fire'' seemed like an opportunity to
achieve commercial success as well. But after that role, no offers
came.
   Perlman withdrew from acting and went through what he recalls as
a purging of his depression.
   ``It was like an incredible dividing line between my childhood
and my adult life,'' he said.
   Now that he is receiving attention as Vincent, Perlman said he
feels as if his career is actually beginning.
   ``If things go the way they should, I see myself ending up as
perhaps the next antihero _ like Jack Nicholson. ... That will be
the ultimate experiment _ to see if anyone is interested in my
face.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
