<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NightStalker Bjt   07-04 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Night Stalker, Bjt,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourth and `Final' Trial Date in Stalker Case Has Come and Gone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after a spate of murderous
bedroom attacks terrorized Californians, the ``Night Stalker'' case
has cost Los Angeles County more than $1 million, and the defendant
still has not come to trial.
   Last Thursday the fourth start date for the trial of Richard
Ramirez had to be abandoned when defense attorneys, who had
promised to be ready, challenged the judge for bias.
   The prosecutor, awaiting a ruling on the last-minute defense
motion to remove the judge, says this is ``the last gasp'' of delay
he can envision.
   ``I have high hopes,'' said Deputy District Attorney P. Philip
Halpin. ``The issue is straightforward. It should be decided by the
time we come back to court on July 7.''
   He said the trial could start immediately after that. But even
if it does begin in July, both sides have estimated that jury
selection could take up to eight months.
   Two defense lawyers, who have been berated by the judge and by
Halpin for being dilatory and unprepared, aren't saying what their
next move will be. Arturo and Daniel Hernandez, who are not
related, did not return repeated calls to their San Jose offices
last week.
   Meanwhile, the legal clock is ticking. The defense, in promising
to be ready for trial June 30, did not waive Ramirez' right to a
speedy trial within 10 days of that date.
   ``We intend to start the trial by the 10th of July,'' said
Halpin.
   But Halpin acknowledged that technically, the 10-day limit dates
from the time the motion is resolved. And the defense could still
choose to waive the time limit if the trial must be delayed again.
   The county has spent $1.28 million on court and investigatory
fees, according to the county auditor-controller's office. That
does not include $15,000 a month for Ramirez' private jail cell.
   Halpin has worried aloud that witnesses who have waited three
years to testify may become reluctant to relive now distant
memories of nightmarish events if the case is postponed yet again.
   Ramirez, 28, a drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged in Los
Angeles County with 13 counts of murder and 31 other felonies
allegedly committed during a string of night-time assaults in the
summer of 1985.
   Attacks also took place from Mission Viejo in Orange County to
the Lake Merced district of San Francisco.
   The so-called Night Stalker generally entered homes through
unlocked doors and left pentagrams, a symbol often associated with
devil worship, scrawled at some crime scenes and on some victims.
   Ramirez shouted ``Hail Satan'' and flashed a pentagram drawn on
his hand during an early court appearance.
   In their challenge to the judge, the Hernandezes said Superior
Court Judge Michael Tynan showed that he believed Ramirez was a
satanist when he asked if the defendant wished to swear to God or
would rather affirm before testifying at pretrial proceedings.
   The lawyers also say Tynan called them a security risk during a
chambers conference.
   ``Although the defense would have wished that the judge had been
able to overcome his bias and tendencies toward prejudice, it has
become increasingly obvious that Judge Tynan cannot do this,'' the
defense team said in an affidavit.
   When the Hernandezes were hired in late 1985, Municipal Court
Judge Elva Soper advised Ramirez that his counsel did not meet the
court's standards for appointment because they had never tried a
death penalty case before.
   Arturo Hernandez had practiced for two years and Daniel
Hernandez for three years. Their opponent, Halpin, has been a
prosecutor for 23 years and handled many capital cases.
   At one point, Tynan assigned a lawyer to assist the two novice
defense attorneys in completing their pretrial motions. But trial
dates of Sept. 30, Feb. 1 and March 22 had to be postponed. One
delay was due to an appellate court ruling giving the defense
access to massive police records which had to be compiled for them.
   ``We've been delayed too long,'' Halpin said after a brief
hearing Thursday. ``This is about the last gasp. We're ready to
go.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
