<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Elections Bjt   07-04 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Elections, Bjt,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ruling Party's Credibility To Be Challenged In Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MO3,4 of June 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party,
which has dominated Mexican politics for almost 60 years, faces a
tough test Wednesday in which its credibility is at stake.
   Few doubt that the the PRI will win in the July 6 presidential
elections.
   The question is whether this party, which has monopolized past
contests, will emerge with a landslide victory or clinch barely
enough votes to continue its mandate.
   The PRI has defied political logic by never losing a
presidential election or gubernatorial race in any of Mexico's 31
states since it was founded in 1929. But it also has been accused
of stuffing ballot boxes to give itself almost incredible
victories, with anywhere from 74 to 95 percent of the vote.
   This time, party officials privately admit that they would be
satisfied with 50 percent of the vote.
   The PRI is under pressure both from its members and the
opposition to change the system that has kept many poor Mexicans
politically passive, although it has pushed the economy to grow.
   But many Mexicans were angered by the economic crises of the
1970s and early 1980s, which they believe were brought on by the
party's inept administration, reckless borrowing and brazen
corruption.
   As a result, President Miguel De la Madrid has spent his six
years in office trying to control inflation and a foreign debt now
exceeding $100 billion, and to push up the Mexican peso, whose
value dropped from 23 to the dollar in 1980 to 2,300 to the dollar
this week.
   De la Madrid has managed to pull inflation down to 36 percent
for the first five months of this year, compared to a record 159
percent in 1987.
   Neverthless, his party is virtually under political siege.
   ``The erosion, discredit and lack of credibility of the
political system is such that even if it wins the elections, its
capacity to govern will depend on how it wins,'' wrote political
analyst Jorge Castaneda.
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, a certain winner as the presidential
candidate of the PRI, is a Harvard-educated economist who sounds
like a reformist pointing out the vices of the system. Once
elected, de Gortari's term will last until 1994.
   
   In his campaign, de Gortari speaks of the need to democratize a
system his party has run since 1929 and to admit what he calls
``our defeats'' at the polls.
   ``We are going to lead the democratic reform that the nation
demands,'' he said recently in a speech.
   The balding, mustachioed de Gortari, presents himself as part of
a more dynamic generation of PRI leaders.
   But Manuel J. Clouthier, the second major presidential candidate
and a member of the rightist National Action Party, blames the PRI
for Mexico's economic problems and hammers away at corruption in
the administration.
   Clouthier, a bearded businessman from the northwestern coastal
state of Sinalosa, is demanding changes in the name of the middle
class.
   ``The group in power since 1929 has failed and has lost its
opportunity,'' Clouthier says. ``They can't present themselves as
the saviors of today. They are the same people who have brought us
to the situation in which we find ourselves.''
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a dissident who broke with the PRI last
year, is the third major presidential candidate and represents the
National Democratic Front, an alliance of disaffected leftist
groups. A former governor of the central state of Michoacan,
Cardenas unsuccessfully tried to reform the PRI before abandoning
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
