<HEAD>TV Maven Says Real Estate Buying All A Game</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin, whose career has included stints
as a singer, talk show host, game show producer and more recently
real estate mogul, says buying and selling property is a lot like a
game.
   Griffin, who began his career in 1949 as a singer in the Freddy
Martin band, entered the real estate business after Coca-Cola
bought his Merv Griffin Productions for an estimated $250 million.
   ``I had an important life decision to make,'' Griffin said in
the August issue of Life magazine. ``I could have sat around and
collected the monies from various investments, spent the rest of my
life clipping coupons. But I thought, `No, no no. There's got to be
another career.'''
   ``To me,'' said the 63-year-old Griffin, ``retirement is the
choice after death.''
   ``What I am doing now is fun,'' said Griffin, who recently won
control of Donald Trump's Resorts International in a hostile
takeover and bought the Beverly Hilton Hotel.
   ``I love the gamesmanship,'' said Griffin. ``This may sound
strange, but it parallels the game shows I've been involved in.''
Griffin helped create television's popular ``Wheel of Fortune'' and
``Jeopardy!''
   His real-life conquests apparently have inspired him. Griffin
says he is working on a new show based on the game Monopoly.
</TEXT>
