<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Robeson-Indians     07-04 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robeson-Indians,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing To Be Held Tuesday For Two Robeson County Indians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA WAGGONER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge will hold a hearing Tuesday to set
conditions for releasing two Tuscarora Indians who have been held
without bond for five months since a newspaper office takeover,
defense attorney William Kunstler said Monday.
   ``We tried to get them out today (Monday),'' Kunstler said in a
telephone interview from New York. ``We thought Independence Day
would be a great day for them to come out.''
   But the hearing could not be scheduled until Tuesday at the
federal courthouse in New Bern because of the holiday, Kunstler
said.
   Eddie Hatcher, 30, and Timothy Jacobs, 19, are set to go to
trial July 11 on federal charges of hostage-taking and
manufacturing illegal firearms. The two are charged with holding up
to 20 people hostage Feb. 1 at The Robesonian newspaper office in
Lumberton in Robeson County, near the South Carolina line.
   They are being held at the Craven County Jail in New Bern, 120
miles east of Lumberton.
   Conditions of release were discussed Monday during a conference
call that involved Kunstler and Bob Warren, a defense attorney from
the Christic Institute South in Carrboro, N.C.; the U.S. Attorney's
Office in North Carolina; and U.S. District Court Judge Terence
Boyle, Kunstler said.
   ``They will be released,'' he said. ``The circuit court has
ordered it.''
   The terms of release discussed in the conference call include
that the two stay out of Robeson County; that they live with
friends or relatives; and that they not violate any aspect of the
law even though they may consider it symbolic free speech, Kunstler
said.
   ``These are the conditions we proposed to the judge months
ago,'' he said. ``They are our conditions.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Stuart Bruce would not comment on
the conference call, which Kunstler said came after the 4th U.S.
Court of Appeals ruled Thursday that a federal magistrate failed to
hold a detention hearing within the required five days.
   Kunstler said he received a copy of the opinion Saturday. The
appeals court in Richmond, Va., was closed for the holiday weekend
and the ruling could not be independently confirmed.
   ``The Court of Appeals minced no words in its opinion,'' he said
Monday, adding that the court called the detention ``a flat
violation'' of the time requirements.
   The two men had gone before Magistrate Wallace Dixon on Feb. 2
but didn't have their detention hearing until Feb. 17. At that
time, Dixon ordered them held without bond. Boyle upheld the
decision at a hearing in April.
   Kunstler said Dixon contends the two Indians waived their
detention hearing, saying they were afraid to be released. But
Kunstler said defendants cannot legally waive their own hearing.
   Although the trial is scheduled to begin July 11, Kunstler said
there probably will be a continuance. He also said he would try to
have the trial held in the Fayetteville division court, which
includes Robeson County.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
