<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Airliner-HairTrigger     07-04 1029</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Hair Trigger,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Time For Reflection By Commanders In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. commanders in the Persian Gulf are
operating under hair-trigger rules of engagement designed to
prevent unexpected attacks on American warships, such the one on
the USS Stark last year that killed 37 servicemen.
   ``The number one obligation of the commanding officer of a ship
or units is the protection of his own people,'' said the chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe, defending the
Navy against charges that the USS Vincennes overreacted Sunday when
it shot down an Iranian jetliner carring 290 people.
   The imperative for self-defense _ combined with the cramped
quarters in the Gulf, the introduction there of advanced weapons
that allow adversaries to kill quickly from a great distance, and
the large number of on-again off-again combatants _ have produced
an explosive situation.
   Pentagon officials refuse to spell out publicly the rules of
engagement, the standing orders under which commanders are
authorized to open fire. Whatever they are, the commander of the
Vincennes apparently is convinced he followed them.
   Pentagon sources, who spoke on condition they not be further
identified, said Monday that the commander, Capt. Will C. Rogers
III, had sent a message to his superiors stressing that he had
followed procedures and would make the same decisions if faced
again with the situation.
   The sources were unable to provide quotes from the
communication, which they described as secret.
   Despite official silence, events and statements over the past 14
months have given a fairly detailed picture of when American forces
will shoot.
   ``We can go on what is known as hostile intent. That is to say
if a fellow has a weapons system aimed at us and we have a pretty
high assurance that he going to shoot at us, we can take it out,''
the commander of U.S. forces in the region, Marine Corps Gen.
George B. Crist told reporters last Thursday.
   Crowe said U.S. commanders ``do not have to be shot at before
responding,'' a condition that was made known in the form of a
Notice to Airmen, or NOTAM, to all nations and parties involved in
the Gulf, including commercial air air carriers operating there.
   Rogers said in an interview before sailing his ship to the
Persian Gulf that ``there is a very clear-cut set of engagement
rules which we go by and we're certainly not there to initiate
hostilities.''
   Since the U.S. Navy increased its presence in the Persian Gulf
in the spring of 1987, and began to escort reflagged Kuwaiti
tankers last summer, Crowe said, ``We are, of course, constantly
surveying and reviewing not only the circumstances under which we
operate, but also the rules of engagement.''
   ``We do not discuss the rules in detail,'' he told reporters
Sunday after the airliner was shot down, ``but this obviously will
put increased emphasis on such a review.''
   Until Sunday, the greatest loss of life in a single incident
involving the U.S. Navy in the Gulf came from what was later
described as a mistaken attack by an Iraqi fighter which fired two
Exocet missiles into the unsuspecting cruiser USS Stark on May 17,
1987.
   The explosions and fire killed 37 American seaman and ended the
careers of the Stark's commander, Capt. Glenn R. Brindel, and other
senior officers, who were severely criticized and forced to retire.
   On Sunday, one of those chastised officers defended Rogers,
saying the Vincennes had no choice but to fend off what appeared to
be a attacking warplane.
   ``If the plane was unfortunate enough to be flying toward the
Vincennes while the Vincennes was engaging Iranian patrol boats ...
I'm not surprised this kind of thing would happen,'' said Basil E.
Moncrief.
   According to the Pentagon account, Rogers followed what appeared
to be carefully laid out procedures. The sophisticated Aegis radar
and tracking system aboard the Vincennes, one of the most advanced
ships in the Navy, detected an aircraft approaching from Iranian
airspace at 10:47 a.m. local time (2:47 EDT), officials said.
   At the time, the Vincennes was exchanging fire with three
Iranian Boghammer gunboats, 43-foot-long vessels that Iran has used
to attack tankers, they said.
   ``One of the most difficult problems is from a radar blip,
particularly from a head-on target, to identify the type of
aircraft,'' said Crowe.
   If the Vincennes had a side view of the plane, or had more time,
it might not have mistaken the airbus, which is 177 feet long, for
an F-14, which is 62 feet long, Pentagon officials said.
   The Vincennes broadcast three warnings on a civilian emergency
network, which airliners normally monitor, and four warnings on a
frequency normally monitored by warplanes, Crowe said.
Additionally, he said the ship intercepted and analyzed
``electronic indications'' which the admiral declined to discuss in
detail.
   The approaching aircraft appeared to descend and accelerate, as
would a warplane preparing to launch an anti-ship missile, and was
declared ``hostile'' four minutes after it was spotted by radar, he
said. Three minutes later, when the plane was about nine miles from
the Vincennes, the American warship fired. The first visual
sighting of the plane came with the impact of at least one of the
missiles, when the aircraft was about six miles from the Vincennes,
said Crowe.
   Crist indicated to reporters last week that the rules of
engagement varied depending on the threat, and that the biggest
threats were perceived to be anti-ship missiles, such as the
Chinese-made Silkworm.
   Use of a weapon like the Silkworm, he suggested, would call for
destruction not only of the missile, but the battery that fired it.
   ``If they fire a Silkworm at me we can go get them,'' he said.
   But in recent months the Iranians have avoided attacking U.S.
forces, making it doubly hard for American commanders to guess
whether they may be about to face hostile fire.
   ``They have been most circumspect,'' said Crist. ``They've been
very careful not to antagonize us. We had an (Iranian) F-4 come out
the other day ... and our ships challenged him, (and) he said, `I'm
on my way to engage an Iraqi.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880704-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     07-04 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Expresses Deep Regrets Over Downing of Iranian Jetliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush on Monday
voiced regret over the accidental destruction of an Iranian
jetliner by a U.S. warship, but said the tragic incident would not
alter U.S. policy in the Persian Gulf.
   ``My respects to families and loved ones of those who lost
lives, but life goes on, our mission goes on and the world keeps
turning,'' Bush said as he campaigned through the Midwest.
   The all-but-certain Republican nominee echoed the views of
President Reagan who said U.S. warships will remain in the gulf in
the wake of Sunday's U.S. missile attack on an Iran Air Airbus with
290 people aboard.
   ``We want peace in the gulf, but we also want the right of
navigation in international waters,'' Reagan told reporters upon
his return to the White House from a weekend at Camp David.
   The vice president, who broke his silence on the incident, said
he ``would just reject the comparison'' to the Soviet Union's
destruction of a Korean airliner that strayed into Soviet airspace
in 1983.
   ``This plane was warned. This was flying in a combat zone,''
Bush said. He claimed the two episodes were ``totally separate,
totally different.''
   Bush also said he would not suspend his presidential campaigning
because of the gulf tragedy, telling reporters, ``there is nothing
I can be doing about this matter in Washington, D.C.''
   However, the vice president planned to return to Washington late
Monday after participating in Independence Day festivities in
Wyandotte, a Detroit suburb, and in two other Midwestern cities.
Aides said Bush had been in telephone contact with military
advisers and would attend a White House briefing on Tuesday.
   Bush learned of the attack Sunday morning while attending church
services in Kennebunkport, Maine, the seacoast town where he has a
vacation home. He later participated in a conference call with
Reagan and senior White House officials, said Craig Fuller, Bush's
chief of staff.
   Bush told reporters at Detroit International Airport he was
saddened by Sunday's events.
   ``Obviously, as we celebrate our great national holiday our
hearts go out to the loved ones and families of those who were lost
and also (hearts) go out to those kids, those young Americans who
are defending freedom half way around the world,'' he said.
   En route to a Fourth of July parade in this Detroit suburb, Bush
adhered closely to the Reagan administration's support for the
captain of the USS Vincennes and said he thinks most Americans
share his feelings.
   ``It appears the captain of that ship followed the rules and did
what he had to do, protect American life,'' Bush said.
   Questioned as to why the warship's sophisticated radar equipment
could not distinguish between the wide-bodied airliner and the
smaller F-14 fighter, Bush, a World War II pilot, responded
testily, ``Ever been in combat. Combat is quite different than the
laboratory.''
   And asked about Iranian threats of retaliation, Bush said,
``From time to time, Iran makes such threats, but our people are
alert. We can't be deterred by threats.''
   The Republican candidate said he didn't think the episode would
figure in the presidential race, saying, ``Americans are together
on this.''
   He also said there was no reason to halt campaign activity
because of the tragedy. ``This is a national holiday. It is
appropriate that we celebrate it,'' he said.
   The vice president said he did not think the downing of the
commercial airliner is ``more significant than other incidents, but
it is significant.'' Bush cited the loss of U.S. servicemen aboard
the USS Stark, which was hit by an Iraqi missile on May 17, 1987,
as a significant incident in the gulf.
   Bush was also scheduled to participate in an Independence Day
celebration in Elmwood, Ill., a Chicago suburb, and attend a rally
for new U.S. citizens and watch an airshow in St. Louis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
