<DOCNO> AP880704-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Khomeini Bjt   07-04 1036</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Khomeini, Bjt,1076</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Daughter Gives Rare Insight Into His Home Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini reads the
Koran, Islam's holy book, seven times a day, takes the radio with
him to the bathroom to keep up with the news, and is an obsessive
clock watcher, his daughter, Zahra, says.
   In a talk earlier this month to students at Roshd High School in
Tehran, she gave an insight into the home life of Iran's
revolutionary patriarch.
   ``His self-discipline is unbelievable. You wouldn't believe it
unless you saw it for yourself,'' she told the children.
   The talk was published in the Islamic Revolution Martyr
Foundation's magazine and reprinted in an unofficial
English-language newsletter received recently in Nicosia.
   Khomeini's daughter, whose married name is Mostafavi, made no
mention of the 82-year-old leader's health, reported to be
deteriorating.
   Mrs. Mostafavi, 49, painted a portrait of a loving, if
demanding, father who used to take his family on summer vacations
in the mountains before he became a revolutionary leader banished
into exile by the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   That's a far cry from his public image of the stern, unsmiling
zealot whose fundamentalist Moslem revolution eliminated former
allies and brought Iran into a seemingly endless war with Iraq.
   Mrs. Mostafavi was quoted as saying her father observes a strict
schedule at his home in the north Tehran suburb of Jamaran and
becomes so engrossed in his studies of the Koran or affairs of
state that he sometimes doesn't talk for hours.
   ``He's so punctual that if he doesn't turn up for lunch at
exactly 1:20 p.m., everyone gets worried,'' she said. ``He
regulates his day in such a way that he turns up for lunch at
exactly that time.''
   She said: ``To him, such things as `I sleep whenever I like' or
`I feel like going to sleep' are meaningless. He eats exactly on
time. He wakes up exactly on time. He goes to bed exactly on time.''
   Mrs. Mostafavi noted: ``He goes walking three times a day, each
time for exactly 20 minutes. When he gets back, he looks at his
watch to see if it's been 20 minutes.''
   ``If it's not, he turns around and takes a few more steps just
to make everything complete.''
   She said that Khomeini, engrossed in some activity or other,
sometimes won't even talk to her when she goes to his study.
   ``Just because I'm his daughter doesn't mean that we have a
conversation each time,'' she said. ``I go into the room and say
hello and just sit there because he's either listening to the radio
or watching television or reading letters and reports.
   ``He's not free even for a minute. Even in the bathroom, he has
the radio with him.''
   She said Khomeini's income includes ``ta'aroufi,'' or personal
gifts from well-wishers and admirers to show their respect for his
religious standing.
   She said these gifts include ``some money or gold'' which he
sometimes spends ``on home expenses.''
   Mrs. Mostafavi said her father's income ``is a lot. He usually
received a lot of gold ... but he spends moderately ... He leads a
simple life.''
   Referring to Khomeini's religious devotion, she said: ``He reads
the Koran seven times a day at special times. There are also prayer
books he reads and he doesn't care who's there.''
   Diplomats who have visited Khomeini at home said he regularly
listens to the British Broadcasting Corporation's Persian Service,
a habit that dates back to his exile in Iraq from 1963 to 1978.
   Khomeini was expelled from Iraq in 1978 and went to France. He
lived in Paris for four months before returning to Iran in 1979,
when his Islamic revolution toppled the shah.
   The visitors said Khomeini often wears a small transistor radio
on a cord around his neck. He also is reported to be a fan of
Mickey Mouse and often watches cartoons on a videocassete recorder.
   Mrs. Mostafavi is one of Khomeini's three daughters. His son,
Ahmed, 48, is one of his closest advisers and carefully screens the
hundreds of people who want to visit him every day.
   Diplomats who have been based in Tehran said Ahmed only allows
two or three people to see his father every day, usually at
breakfast or lunch, so as not to tire him.
   Another son, Mustafa, died in Iraq during Khomeini's exile there.
   Khomeini married Khanom Batool Saqafi in the Iranian holy city
of Qom when he was a 29-year-old theology student and she was a
teen-ager. Mrs. Mostafavi said her mother, who is rarely seen in
public, is ``very sedate and cool. She went with him everwhere. In
all that time, she has never complained or grouched.''
   Despite his unyielding religious and political beliefs, Mrs.
Mostafavi said Khomeini ``is very easy with his children. He has 14
grandchildren and a great-grandchild now. He allows the children a
large degree of freedom.
   ``He doesn't preach to the grownups that they should do this or
that. He sets examples by his actions ... but he gets very angry at
the slightest act forbidden by religion.
   ``He tells us not to waste things. Once I cooked him something
and burned it. I put it in front of him, but he didn't eat it.
   ``He said it was bad. I asked jokingly, `but you shouldn't be
ungrateful for the blessing of God?'
   ``He anwered back: `Is it me who is ungrateful or is it you who
have done such a thing to God's blessing?'
   ``He's somewhat formal with people other than his family. But
he's very kind to his family.''
   Khomeini returned to Tehran Feb. 1, 1979, from exile in Paris to
a tumultuous welcome after more than 14 years in exile.
   Ten days later, when the revolutionaries took over the symbols
of government, the shah's palace, state buildings and army
barracks, Mrs. Mostafavi said she was with Khomeini listening to
the radio.
   ``Suddenly he jumped up and said, `It's over! It's over!' she
said.
   ``The radio and television station had been seized. I realized
that meant the fall of the regime. I've never seen such joy on his
face as I did then,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
