<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0555 07-04 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0555,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Stone Troops, Army Closes West Bank Schools</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with five arrests, scattered
stoning in the West Bank; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Releasing new
...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Arab students
pelted soldiers with rocks and blocked a main road Monday in
Bethlehem, and the army slapped a three-day closure order on all
West Bank schools.
   Troops in this biblical town fired tear gas and dozens of
students were overcome by the gas, hospital officials said.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, meanwhile, announced the nearly
7-month-old Arab uprising in the occupied territories had cost the
Defense Ministry $162 million and Israel's economy was in danger if
the rebellion continued, Israel radio said.
   The radio reported scattered incidents of stone throwing in the
West Bank and Arab east Jerusalem, where Arab protesters briefly
erected a roadblock on the main commercial thoroughfare.
   Police arrested five Palestinian schoolgirls for allegedly
stoning Israeli cars near the east Jerusalem neighborhood of
Silwan, the radio said.
   Releasing new figures on incidents of unrest inside Israel,
Police Commissioner David Krauss said Arab nationalists were
responsible for 114 out of 210 forest and pasture arsons.
   Krauss said more than 1,000 protests broke out inside Israel in
the last three months, including 730 demonstrations in the
Jerusalem area and 51 firebomb attacks.
   He said 900 Arabs had been arrested on a variety of charges,
including 55 suspected of arson.
   In Bethlehem, five miles south of Jerusalem, hundreds of
students demonstrated on the main road, hurling stones at troops
who responded with tear gas and rubber bullets.
   In an effort to limit student participation in the uprising, the
army announced it would close all Palestinian schools in the West
Bank for three days starting Tuesday.
   The move was timed to coincide with a PLO call to rename all
Arab schools with more nationalistic names on that day, said Brig.
Gen. Shaike Erez, head of Israel's military administration in the
West Bank.
   The order was the first West Bank-wide shutdown of Arab schools
since the area's 800 schools were reopened on June 6 after a
four-month closure.
   At the height of the uprising in February, the army closed 1,200
schools attended by 475,000 students in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Erez said he hoped closing schools again would ``bring home to
students and parents that the current level of disturbances is
unacceptable.''
   But Bethlehem high school senior Adnan Mohammed blamed the army
presence in the territories for the student protests and said they
would continue as long as Israeli occupation continued.
   ``There is no atmosphere to study, with soldiers at the entrance
to schools,'' Mohammed said, adding that only 19 of the 30 students
in his class showed up for studies.
   ``Where are the others? One was shot and killed during the
uprising, four are in jail and the other six are under curfew in
the Deheishe refugee camp. Nobody is in the mood to study,''
Mohammed said.
   History teacher Hisham Mughrabi said students were commited to
calls by underground leaders to hold protests and would not heed
admonishments from school adminstrators not to demonstrate.
   ``It used to be the teacher got respect, but that's all changed.
If we tell them not to demonstrate, they say it's the leadership's
order. We can't argue with them,'' Mughrabi said.
   An Associated Press reporter saw one Bethlehem school that was
renamed ``Intefadeh,'' or Arabic for ``Uprising,'' apparently in
compliance with the call to give schools more nationalistic names.
</TEXT>
