<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   07-04 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Killed in Factional Fighting in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting between rival Palestinian
guerrilla groups Monday killed 24 people as artillery shells
pulverized the Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camp, according to police.
   They said 67 others were wounded in the battle between Col.
Saeed Mousa's Syrian-backed Fatah-Uprising and Fatah guerrillas
loyal to Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   That raised the known casualty toll since fighting broke out May
1 to at least 151 killed and 594 wounded.
   Bodies littered the terrain along the camp's edges as the two
warring factions launched a series of attacks and counterattacks,
witnesses said.
   ``The shelling is the worst we've had in years,'' said a woman
who took advantage of an afternoon lull in the bombardment to flee
Bourj el-Barajneh.
   Sultan Abul-Ainen, Fatah's commander in Bourj el-Barajneh, said
25 people, most of them women and children, were wounded when a
160mm mortar slammed into entrance of a bomb shelter.
   Police said they were among the 67 wounded in today's fighting.
   The fighting shattered a weeklong lull in the inter-Palestinian
war for control of the Beirut camps.
   Mousa's fighters overran the nearby Chatilla camp June 27 and
had vowed to move into Bourj el-Barajneh in an attempt to crush
Arafat's forces in the Lebanese capital.
   At times, shells and rockets rained at a rate of 20 a minute on
the sprawling Shantytown on Beirut's southern outskirts, police
said.
   They said the fighting forced the closing of the Beirut airport
highway, which abuts Bourj el-Barajneh. Flight schedules were not
affected and travelers got to the airport through sidestreets.
   Columns of black smoke billowed from the camp. Mousa's gunners,
deployed in Syrian-controlled hills overlooking Beirut, hammered
the camp with 120mm and 160mm mortars, rockets and 106mm recoilless
guns, police reported.
   They said Fatah guerrillas responded with 62mm mortars and
rocket-propelled grenades.
   Abul-Ainen, Fatah's commander, said his men repulsed 13 attempts
by the dissident fighters to push into the camp in a fierce
eight-hour confrontation.
   Abul-Ainen, reached by telephone in Bourj el-Barajneh, said at
least five corpses of the attackers ``lay on the battlefield. The
dissidents could not evacuate them due to the intensity of the
fighting.''
   The fall of Chatilla was a serious setback for Arafat, who has
called on Arab leaders to help end the fighting. Abul-Ainen said
his fighters are determined to defend Bourj el-Barajneh ``to the
last man.''
   ``We warn these collaborators that Bourj el-Barajneh will not
face the same fate as Chatilla,'' he said.
   Fatah, the largest group of Arafat's Palestine Liberation
Organization, dislodged Mousa's followers from Bourj el-Barajneh
and the nearby Chatilla refugee camp in fighting over the past two
months.
   The dissidents regrouped along the edges of the camps and
overran Chatilla after a 13-hour battle that demolished the
shantytown and displaced hundreds of refugees.
   Libyan mediators supervised the evacuation of about 150 Arafat
loyalists from Chatilla to Fatah bases the port city of Sidon, 25
miles south of Beirut.
   Fatah and other PLO officials said 80 percent of Bourj
el-Barajneh has been knocked down in bombardments in the past 60
days. Only 3,000 of 20,000 residents remain in the camp.
   Scores of civilians fled the camp during the weeklong lull in
fighting after Chatilla fell.
   The camps have been largely devastated by fighting that began
when Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982, besieged West Beirut and
hammered the shantytowns with air raids and shellfire for months.
   Syrian-backed Lebanese Shiite Moslems besieged the Beirut camps
in 1985, pounding them for more than two years in a failed attempt
to prevent Arafat from rebuilding the power base he lost when
Israel drove the PLO out of Beirut in 1982.
   Mousa, who has vowed to chase the PLO out of Lebanon again,
broke away from the organization in 1983. The Syrian government
backed the mutiny by radicals opposed to Arafat, and Mousa set up
his headquarters in the Syrian capital of Damascus.
   The Beirut fighting has flared despite a reconciliation between
Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad in Damascus in April to end
their 5-year-old feud. But since the fighting erupted Arafat has
accused the Syrian government of fomenting the battle in order to
assert its control over all of Beirut.
</TEXT>
