<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     07-04 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Offer Amnesty to Deserters in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Monday offered an amnesty to
soldiers who turned against their country during the Red Army's
8{-year intervention in Afghanistan, the country's chief legal
officer said.
   ``Those who could not resist hostile propaganda, who failed to
withstand suffering and privations of captivity and committed
offenses damaging our state, all of them will be amnestied out of
supreme considerations of socialist humanism,'' Prosecutor General
Alexander Sukharev told a news briefing.
   Asked if the conditions included deserters, Sukharev said they
would be included with those who suffered because of the ``extreme
conditions'' of the war in Afghanistan, to whom the amnesty will be
applied.
   It was not immediately clear if the amnesty was unconditional,
or whether there would be a review procedure.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979, replaced
one pro-Soviet government with another, and remained there to help
fight anti-Marxist insurgents. The Soviet military said in late May
that more than 13,000 soldiers had been killed in Afghanistan and
more than 35,000 wounded.
   Sukharev said the Soviet Union had identified 312 soldiers who
had been taken prisoner during the war, and had established that
about a third of them had died, many of them in the act of trying
to escape.
   ``Some of them were shot on the spot, some of them were tortured
to death,'' he said.
   Those who remain captive ``are subject to torture. They are
manacled, they are under psychological pressure, including scant
food supplies,'' he said.
   Most of the 200 are on Pakistani territory in the hands of
Afghan guerrilla groups, but an undetermined number are in the
United States, Canada and Western Europe, the prosecutor general
said.
   He said he did not know how many soldiers could be classified as
deserters.
   Sukharev said in offering the amnesty, the Presidium of the
Supreme Soviet, the country's highest executive body, wanted to
refute what he said were rumors in the West that prisoners of war
and deserters would face severe punishment if they returned to the
Soviet Union.
   The Presidium already has pardoned one soldier who was punished
for desertion, he said.
   Prisoners of war who return ``will enjoy in full measure all
political, social and all other rights guaranteed by the
Constitution of the U.S.S.R. to Soviet citizens,'' he said.
   The legal official said his country was ``using all channels to
obtain the release of our soldiers and bring them back home.''
   He appealed to the United States, Pakistan and other countries
to help Soviet soldiers who are on their territory to return home.
   The Soviet Union began pulling its 100,000 soldiers out of
Afghanistan on May 15, and units still there awaiting withdrawal
are not taking part in offensive operations.
   Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov, commander of the Soviet force in
Afghanistan, told reporters in Moscow last week that 20,000
soldiers already had left the country.
   According to an agreement signed in Geneva on April 14, the
Soviet force is to be withdrawn completely by Feb. 15, 1989.
   However, the Soviet Union and Afghanistan repeatedly have
accused Pakistan of continuing to aid anti-Marxist guerrillas, and
the Soviets say they reserve the right to alter the withdrawal
schedule because of it.
   The Soviet Union has appealed to Pakistan several times in
recent weeks to help return Soviet prisoners of war held by the
guerrillas.
   Return of missing Soviet soldiers has become an issue of serious
concern, discussed in the official media and by top Soviet leaders
in public forums since the withdrawal began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880704-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-USIA-Politics Bjt   07-04 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USIA-Politics, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overseas Speakers Focusing On American Election Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stung by 1984 charges that it blacklisted
liberals, the U.S. Information Agency this year is sending both
Republicans and Democrats around the world to speak about the U.S.
political system and the presidential election campaign.
   The effort, part of a $1.7 million overseas speakers program run
by USIA, involves about 120 speakers including political
professionals from both parties, election officials, university
political scientists, lawyers and writers.
   Four years ago, the American Participants Program _ known as
AmParts _ came under fire, accused of rejecting 38 proposed
speakers on partisan or ideological grounds. But Capitol Hill
overseers say the program's problems appear to have been dealt with
adequately.
   ``We don't have any complaints that are pending now,'' said Rep.
Dan Mica, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on international operations. ``I think it's a
tremendous program, but it was abused for a while. We've
straightened that out.''
   Joseph O'Connell, an official at USIA's public liaison office,
said the agency tries to take a politically balanced approach to
selecting speakers for the program.
   He said that ``for obvious reasons we don't want to make it look
like we're leaning toward (Vice President George) Bush,'' who is
all but certain to be the Republican nominee running against
Democrat Michael Dukakis in the fall presidential race.
   In some cases, USIA's approach this election year has led to
sending of Democrat-Republican teams to appear side-by-side before
foreign audiences.
   For example, political consultant Ed Rollins, manager of
President Reagan's 1984 re-election campaign, this month traveled
to West Germany with Les Francis, another consultant who served as
deputy chief of staff in the Carter White House.
   Francis said that during the week-long trip they spoke to
political professionals, academics, students, journalists and
business people in four cities _ Bonn, Hamburg, Nuremberg and
Mannheim.
   He found German audiences already well versed in the basics of
American politics but eager to learn more about the nuances of this
year's campaign.
   ``They can read about what Dukakis might think about the MX or
the Midgetman (mobile missile), or they can read about what George
Bush's resume is in terms of foreign policy experience.
   ``But to get a feel for how these guys conduct their campaigns,
the kind of people around them _ that's ultimately as important to
the presidency as position papers or biographical sketches. And I
think that's what they were interested in as much as anything,''
Francis said.
   Another speaking team involved Thomas Susman, a Washington
attorney active in Democratic politics, and Loren Smith, a
conservative Republican who served as counsel to Reagan's 1980
campaign and is now chief judge of the U.S. Claims Courts. They
spent three weeks in March visiting the Philippines, Pakistan,
Turkey and Egypt.
   Susman noted that ``we went to countries where the party which
is out of power doesn't want to just win the next election, they
want to kill the people in power. They want a new constitution.
They want new forms of government.
   ``And so the example of people from the United States who have
opposing perspectives but who talk rationally about issues and
personalities with each other was something that we were told was
quite impressive,'' he said.
   Other speakers include:
   _Benjamin Ginsburg, director of Cornell University's Institute
for Public Affairs, who traveled to West Germany, Norway, Spain and
Portugal.
   ``You always understand your own politics better from afar,''
Ginsburg said. ``Americans are very ethnocentric. We see the
universe revolving around the United States. And it's very useful
to step outside the United States and see the U.S. through somebody
else's eyes. It freshens your own perspective.''
   _Jerry Hagstrom, author of a recently published book, ``Beyond
Reagan: The New Landscape of American Politics,'' and a
contributing editor of The National Journal, a Washington-based
weekly. He visited Finland, Switzerland and China.
   Hagstrom said his Chinese audiences included ``young scholars
who had just returned from spending five years in the United
States. ... But within the same audience you would have young
graduate students who have never left China. With them you had to
explain what is a caucus and what is a primary.''
   _James Lengle, a professor of government at Georgetown
University, who lectured, gave press interviews and made other
appearances in Australia and Fiji. On Fiji, he said, ``Everyone was
very much confused about how the parties go about picking their
nominees and how actually the president is elected.''
   _Samuel Shipley, chairman of the Delaware Democratic Committee,
who traveled to Denmark, Italy and Iceland. Shipley said he was
impressed at how much less it costs candidates to run for office in
those countries by comparison with the United States, where money
has become ``the cancer of politics.''
   In May 1984, USIA Director Charles Z. Wick appeared before
Mica's international operations subcommittee as it investigated the
blacklisting charges.
   Richard W. McBride, the subcommittee's staff director, said the
panel was satisfied that ``there are now nothing in the way of
political litmus tests being given to the AmParts (participants).''
   ``They really learned a lesson,'' McBride said. ``I think it was
one of the real object lessons to Wick that he could not run that
agency without paying due attention to Congress.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880704-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Corruption     07-04 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Corruption,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Investigators Abused Authority by Publishing
Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators abused their authority by publishing
allegations that some delegates to last week's Communist Party
conference had taken bribes, the Soviet Union's chief law
enforcement officer said Monday.
   But Procurator General Alexander Sukharev said he had not plans
to take action against the investigators or the magazine Ogonyok,
which published their charges June 26.
   Publication of the charges against unidentified delegates caused
a storm of criticism by delegates to the four-day conference that
ended Friday in the Kremlin.
   On Thursday, Ogonyok editor Vitaly Korotich personally turned
over to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev papers that he said
proved the charges. He told the conference that an overlapping
system of party and court control prevented the suspects from being
brought to justice.
   Asked about the case at a news briefing Monday, Sukharev said
the investigators ``abused their authority'' by turning to Ogonyok
with their material.
   ``We have the principle that people are regarded as not guilty
in this country,'' he said. ``This is a constitutional principle.''
   Queried whether that meant he would be taking action against the
magazine, Sukharev said, ``I can say I don't have such an intention
as yet.''
   He said the matter still was being investigated and that his
office should be able to draw its final conclusions soon.
   Ogonoyok said investigators trying to unravel corruption in the
Central Asian republic of Uzbekistan came across evidence that four
delegates to the party conference had taken bribes.
   Stories this year have laid open systematic corruption that led
all the way to Yuri Churbanov, son-in-law of late President Leonid
I. Brezhnev.
   Sukharev said Ogonyok's report was true that some people tried
to block the investigation, but he added that there had been
arrests and convictions of such people.
   Churbanov, who served as first deputy interior minister, faces
trial soon on charges of bribery and abuse of power, the procurator
general said.
</TEXT>
