<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Elections     07-04 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Elections,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Elects Its 1989 Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Radical Civic Union
party overwhelmingly chose Gov. Eduardo Angeloz of Cordoba province
as its presidential candidate in 1989 elections, official returns
showed Monday.
   Angeloz, the handpicked candidate of party leader and President
Raul Alfonsin, on Sunday garnered 593,616 votes, or 88 percent, by
members of the centrist party, according to returns.
   The remaining 12 percent, or 81,088 votes, went to Sen. Luis
Leon of northern Chaco province and Carlos Yeregui.
   Alfonsin by law cannot run for re-election in the 1989
presidential elections.
   Members of the main opposition Justicialist (Peronist) Party
will chose its presidential candidate Saturday between Buenos Aires
province Gov. Antonio Cafiero and Gov. Carlos Menem of La Rioja
province.
   National elections are expected to be held in May or June 1989
to replace Alfonsin, whose election to a six-year term in 1983
ended nearly eight years of rightist military rule.
   Angeloz based his campaign on the need to improve the nation's
inflation-plagued economy, repay the $55 billion foreign debt and
continue Alfonsin's programs for economic deregulation and the
breakup of some state-run companies.
   Angeloz, 56, was one of the few party candidates to survive the
September elections in which Peronist and provincial candidates won
20 of the nation's 22 provincial governorships.
   The Peronists advocate a moratorium on the interest portion of
Argentina's foreign debt, third-largest in the developing world.
</TEXT>
