<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Airliner-KALComparison     07-04 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-KAL Comparison,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says ``Great Difference'' Between KAL, Persian Gulf
Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan asserted Monday ``there was a
great difference'' between the U.S. Navy's destruction of an
Iranian commercial airliner and the Soviet Air Force's 1983
destruction of a Korean Air Lines jet.
   Vice President George Bush concurred. ``This plane was warned,''
he said, speaking of the Iranian jet downed Sunday by missiles from
the Navy cruiser Vincennes in the Strait of Hormuz.
   ``This plane was flying in a combat area. It's totally separate,
totally different,'' Bush told reporters in Wyandotte, Mich.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., a member of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, agreed with Bush and Reagan, saying that unlike the
Korean jet, the Iranian plane had been warned on both civilian and
military frequencies.
   ``There are a lot of differences between the two situations,''
he said in an interview on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
   The comparison between the two incidents was raised immediately
after U.S. officials said the Vincennes, thinking it was shooting
at an Iranian F-14, knocked Iran Air flight 655 into the Persian
Gulf.
   KAL flight 007, a Boeing 747 enroute from Anchorage, Alaska, to
Seoul, South Korea, was shot down by the Soviets on Sept. 1, 1983.
It was hit by an air-to-air missile fired by a Soviet fighter.
   The KAL shootdown was first revealed by the United States, which
released intercepted tape recordings of the Soviet pilot telling
his ground controller that ``the target is destroyed.''
   At the time, Reagan criticized ``the barbarity of the Soviet
government in shooting down an unarmed plane'' and U.S. officials
asserted that the Soviets knew they were shooting at a commercial
airliner.
   The Soviet reaction Monday was less critical. Gennady Gerasimov,
a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, said the Soviets didn't
intend to follow the ``bad example'' of ``wild'' criticism.
   Gerasimov said the U.S. explanation that the Vincinnes mistook
the Iranian plane for an F-14 jet ``appeared to be strange. It
shows American naval officers were not very competent, or to use an
American phrase, trigger-happy.''
   Reagan, asked Monday about comparisons between the two
incidents, repeated the assertion that the Soviets knew they were
targeting a commercial plane. ``Remember the KAL, a group of Soviet
fighter planes went up, identified the plane for what it was and
then proceeded to shoot it down. There's no comparison,'' he said
at the White House.
   The KAL plane was shot down after flying over restricted Soviet
airspace, first above the Kamchatka peninsula and later over
Sakhalin island. The plane crashed into the Sea of Japan.
   Initially, the Soviets refused to admit they had shot at a
commercial plane, asserting that the plane was on a reconnaissance
mission. A week later, the Soviets said they had down the plane,
but said the Soviet pilot had not known it was a commercial craft.
   The Soviets also said the Su-15 jet had fired warning rounds at
the KAL plane before the missile was launched, an assertion first
disputed by the United States and later accepted.
   U.S. officials also asserted that the well-known shape and size
of the 747 made it difficult to mistake for another plane, but the
Soviets said their jet was below and behind the plane and it was
dark, meaning it couldn't be visually identified.
   In addition, the Soviets asserted they were targeting an
American reconnaissance plane and four days after the KAL plane was
downed, U.S. officials admitted that a U.S. RC-135 plane had been
in the general area of the KAL jetliner when the 747 was near the
Kamchatka peninsula. The RC-135 is a military version of the Boeing
707.
   Crowe said Sunday there were ``fundamental differences'' between
the two incidents.
   The KAL shootdown ``was not (in) a war zone, there was not
combat in progress, there was not combat there generally,'' Crowe
said. ``And, secondly, the KAL 007 was not warned in any way, form
or fashion. Nor, as far as I can tell or determine, was any attempt
made to warn.''
   But Crowe's statement is at odds with State Department
statements.
   Although originally asserting the KAL plane wasn't warned, the
State Department later changed that assessment, shortly after the
Soviets asserted there had been warning shots fired.
   On Sept. 11, 1983, the State Department said ``additional
analysis of the tapes'' indicate that the Soviet pilot told his
ground controllers that he had fired his cannons nearly six minutes
before the missiles were launched.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
