<1ST_LINE>d w AM-Airliner-Investigators     07-04 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Investigators,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team Of Inquiry Leaves For Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty left for the
Persian Gulf on Monday to carry out President Reagan's order to
investigate what led the USS Vincennes tp blast an Iranian airliner
from the sky, killing all 290 people aboard.
   Fogarty was heading a six-member team that will interview
officers, including Capt. Will C. Rogers III, 50, commander of the
warship, and review data stored in the the $1 billion ship's
sophisticated Aegis radar and computer system, said Lt. Col. Dave
Titus, a military spokesman.
   Fogarty left at 8 a.m. EDT from MacDill Air Force Base, home of
the U.S. Central Command at MacDill Air Force Base, near Tampa,
Fla., and headquarters for American forces operating in the Persian
Gulf, said Titus, reached by telephone at MacDill.
   Accompanying Fogarty were experts on topics ranging the Aegis
system to operations and ``a lawyer as counsel on matters concering
the Uniform Code of Military Justice,'' said Titus, describing the
presence of the attorney as ``standard.''
   Fogarty is director of plans and policy at Central Command,
according to a biography, which did not list his age. Navy and
Pentagon officials were not immediately able to provide his date of
birth.
   Fogarty is a native of Des Moines, Iowa, and entered the Navy
through the Rerserve Officers Training Course at the Iowa State
University Science and Technology in 1958.
   He graduated from the German Command and Staff College, in
Hamburg, West Germany, in 1971, obtained a masters degree in
international affairs from George Washington University in
Washington, D.C., in 1975, and took part in the international
affairs program at the John F. Kennedy School of Government at
Harvard University in Cambridge, Mass.
   Fogarty commanded destroyer squadrons in the Mediterranean Sea
before being assigned in September 1981 as commanding officer of
the USS New Jersey, the first of the battleships recommissioned
under President Reagan's military buildup.
   He is married to the former Dawn Purvis of Norfolk, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
