<DOCNO> AP880704-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Airliner-USPolicy 1stLd-Writethru a0594 07-04 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-US Policy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says US Ships Will Remain in Gulf Despite Tragedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New lead to include congress backing for president</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan stood fast Monday behind his
policy of defending the right of free navigation in the Persian
Gulf, a position supported by members of Congress as Washington
weighed the impact of the U.S. downing of an Iranian passenger
plane.
   ``We want peace in the Gulf but we also want the right of
navigation of international waters,'' Reagan told reporters after
returning to the White House from a weekend stay at his retreat in
Camp David, Md.
   Asked whether U.S. ships will stay in the Gulf, Reagan said,
``Yes.''
   Meanwhile, members of Congress interviewed Monday generally
agreed that the United States should maintain its military presence
in the Gulf in the wake of Sunday's tragedy, in which 290 lives
were lost.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash., said it would be a
``great mistake'' for the United States to abruptly withdraw its
forces from the Gulf.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, a member of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, said, ``I think our policy to maintain freedom of
navigation of the seas, to respond to third country vessels in
distress upon request is a sound policy and one that will remain. I
do hope that out of this will come a reinvigorated effort to try to
get peace. U.S. interests in the Gulf will best be protected if we
can stop the war.''
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., said the administration should review
its Gulf policy because the next time a tragedy occurs, American
lives may be lost instead of Iranian. He stopped short, however, of
calling for a U.S. withdrawal.
   Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson said the United
States has a right to have military forces stationed in
international waters of the Persian Gulf and ``we should not move
out unilaterally.''
   But he indicated the administration should seek ways to bring
its forces home.
   ``The policy is without end,'' he said. ``To what end are we
there?''
   State Department officials, insisting on anonymity, left open
the possibility that there may be a review of the rules specifying
when U.S. military commanders in the Gulf are permitted to engage
in hostile action.
   The commanders were given greater latitude in taking such action
a year ago after a Iranian jet fired on the frigate USS Stark,
killing 37 crewmen.
   On Monday, the State Department continued to make a studied
effort to avoid the appearance of a crisis atmosphere. There was no
requirement for any major decisions to be made, and all senior
officials took off for the July 4 holiday, the sources said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz was on a holiday weekend
outside of Washington and was planning to go ahead with a planned
2{-week trip to Asia starting Tuesday morning.
   The only reported diplomatic activity was the dispatch of
messages to some foreign governments explaining that the shooting
down of the Iranian plane was a case of mistaken identity, the
officials said.
   It was unclear whether the administration planned an apology
beyond the expression of deep regret Sunday by Adm. William Crowe,
chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, and Reagan's description of
the incident as a ``terrible human tragedy.''
   Another unresolved issue is whether the administration should
pay reparations to families of the victims. Officials recalled that
at the time of the downing of Korean Airlines flight 007 by Soviet
jet fighters, the administration had called on Moscow to pay
compensation to the victims' families.
   Reagan acknowledged that the possibility of Iranian retaliation
was a concern for the administration.
   ``You have to think about that knowing who they are,'' he said.
   Interiewed on the Cable News Network, Mohammad Ja'afar
Mahallati, Iran's ambassdor to the United Nations, called Sunday's
incident a ``blatant act of terrorism'' that should be ``severely
punished.''
   The incident occurred at a time when the United States had been
exploring the possibility of pursuing a dialogue with Iran.
Although U.S. officials had denied reports of secret meetings
between American and Iranian envoys, the two countries are said to
have exchanged messages in recent weeks.
   Robin Wright, an associate at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, said she was told by Iranian officials during
a recent visit to Tehran that the reported exchanges provided a
``hopeful sign'' on a variety of issues.
   But the prospects for any improvement in relations appear dashed
for the time being as a result of the airliner incident.
   The United States broke diplomatic relations with Iran in April
1980 during the period in which American diplomats were held
hostage in Iran.
</TEXT>
