<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark-Rock     07-04 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark-Rock,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glasnost Hasn't Reached European Rock Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSKILDE, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An annual rock extravaganza in this
Danish town drew more than 60,000 people, Western stars and groups
from developing countries, but a major ingredient was still
missing: artists from the flourishing rock scene in the Soviet bloc.
   Three hundred acts played this year's Roskilde Festival,
including Sting, Canadian Bryan Adams, Australia's INXS and Leonard
Cohen of the United States.
   Only two minor acts were from Eastern Europe.
   ``Most of the bands from the communist countries play
10-year-old copies of what we all know,'' said Leif Skov, the
festival's chief booking agent.
   ``However, if we want to develop further, this is a corner
that's not been covered yet,'' Skov told The Associated Press.
   The festival, a major fixture on the European music scene,
closed Sunday with the second-largest attendance in its 18-year
history. Visitors came from Scandinavia, Britain and West Germany,
organizers said.
   Under ``glasnost,'' the openness policy of Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, Soviet rock music is enjoying more freedom than ever,
with many formerly banned bands now playing.
   The estimated number of rock bands in the Soviet Union is
30,000, with about 300 of them playing professionally, a Danish
newspaper reported recently.
   Two Soviet bands were in Denmark in May, said the Amtavisen
Randers daily. Both came in their free time and paid their own
expenses to give promotional performances.
   ``It cost me 1,200 rubles (about $1,400) to be here, but to me
Denmark is worth much more,'' Oleg Gusev, lead singer of the
Leningrad-based rock group Avgust was quoted as saying.
   In previous years the festival has had a few acts from Poland
and some Hungarian bands.
   ``The problem is that it takes at least two years of paperwork
to negotiate a deal in those countries,'' said Nils Traeden, a
talent scout involved in the festival. ``They simply must be more
flexible than that to make it here.''
   Vladimir Merta, a folk singer from Czechoslovakia, made it to
Roskilde after a two-year ban on his music was lifted in his home
country. The other East bloc performance was from a folk group from
Hungary.
   ``This is a marketplace for different ideas and influences, with
enthusiastic crowds pushing you to do things you never tried
before,'' Merta said in an interview.
   Boris Grebenshchikov, the leader of the Soviet band, Aquarium,
recently signed a deal with CBS records to sell his recordings in
the United States.
   ``The way Western audiences perceive rock music is still quite
narrow, and heavily dominated by the American influence,'' Skov
said. ``One of the purposes of this festival is to do something
about it.''
   In previous years some of the profits were contributed to
various charities, including Amnesty International and the
Britain-based World of Music Arts and Dance.
   ``We'd like to have some of the Soviet or East bloc bands
involved in that, too,'' Skov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
