<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LoggerJamboree     07-04 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Logger Jamboree,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Screaming Saws, Flying Sawdust Herald 29th Annual Event</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH FORK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 39.5 seconds, Dyk Fink eased his
prized 1974 McCullough chain saw through a 30-inch log in a shower
of sawdust that left fellow loggers shaking their heads in
admiration.
   ``I come here with a stock engine and I beat 'em all,'' the
56-year-old veteran logger said with a beaming grin.
   Fink became six-time champion of the North Fork Loggers'
Jamboree on Saturday. The event has been held officially for 29
years in these foothills 50 miles north of Fresno.
   For two days the roar of huge chain saws ripped through this
pine and oak-studded canyon in the Sierra Nevada 200 miles
southeast of San Francisco in a celebration of logging, the town's
economic mainstay.
   Proceeds from the jamboree benefit the recreation center;
earlier events raised enough money to buy the 11-acre community
center site.
   ``This is one of the better shows, I tell ya,'' said Herb
Punkin, 57, who's made the circuit of loggers' jamborees up and
down the West Coast.
   During Saturday's pro-am competition, Fink was a hometown
favorite. He and partner Doug Betty, competing in the stock team
saw, sliced a 30-inch log in 1 minute 46.54 seconds and cut through
an 18-inch log with a double-handsaw in 29.95 seconds.
   ``He's the Paul Bunyan of the town,'' observed John Somerville,
another competitor.
   Fink, who resembles a jovial Jonathan Winters, showed his style
in the ``jackpot'' or working chain saw event. After noisily
warming up his saw, Fink turned it off and waited for an official's
starting cue.
   First, he bored the 32-inch blade through the middle of the log,
then cut downward and then back up to finish the first cut, as a
plume of sawdust flew onto an official's T-shirt. Just as a round
of freshly cut lumber hit the dirt, Fink had the saw moving down
for the second cut.
   Three officials with electronic stopwatches, sitting in the dirt
arena, clocked Fink's fluid movement. When the second cut fell
down, Fink pulled back the power tool to the cheers of several
hundred spectators, clustered in the shade of large sugar pines.
   Later, under the shade of the announcer's booth, Fink received
hearty slaps on his sweat-drenched work shirt.
   On Sunday the pros arrived from logging towns all over
California to compete for $2,500 in prize money. Among the events
was hurling a double-butted axe 20 feet at a thick pine round. A
logger who hits the bullseye, a full beer can snugly tucked into
the center, sets off a gusher of white beer foam.
   Other events included ladies power saw, tree falling, hand
chopping and ``Jack and Jill,'' or men and women teamed up with a
six-foot hand saw.
</TEXT>
