<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VietnamMemorial     07-04 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam Memorial,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Immigrant Wins Competition To Design Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLMDEL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese immigrant who fled Saigon just
before it fell won a competition Monday to design New Jersey's
Vietnam Veterans Memorial, and he thanked American soldiers for
rescuing his family.
   ``I feel like I've done something good,'' Hien T. Nguyen said at
a ceremony on the grassy knoll at the Garden State Arts Center
where the memorial will be built.
   ``I want to thank the country for taking us in and making us
Americans,'' said Nguyen, 35, an architect from Marlboro whose
entry was selected from 425 proposals.
   Speaking of the nation's Vietnam veterans, he said, ``If not for
them, I might not be here today. They gave us new life. We are the
lucky ones.''
   Soon after, he announced that he was donating his $5,000
winner's check to fund efforts to find and return soldiers missing
in action and reunite Amerasian children with their American
parents.
   Nguyen's memorial design features a 9-foot-high panel of black
granite lining the interior of a 200-foot-diameter oval. The
granite will be inscribed with the names of 1,419 New Jersey
residents killed in Vietnam and 63 missing in action. A New Jersey
oak tree will stand in the center of the memorial.
   About 200 veterans and their families at the ceremony applauded
Nguyen's work and some in uniforms embraced him.
   Sal Mione, a veteran who was on the committee that selected
Nguyen's design, said the memorial would ``start the healing and
bring together New Jersey veterans the way the Vietnam Memorial in
Washington did for American veterans.''
   Nguyen, who became a U.S. citizen five years ago, was evacuated
from Saigon in an American airlift on April 30, 1975, with his
mother and sister. They were taken to a refugee camp in Arkansas
before Nguyen moved to Blacksburg, Va., where his brother Han was a
student at Virginia Polytechnic Institute, which Nguyen also
attended.
   ``I think it has special meaning,'' Han Nguyen, 37, said of his
brother's design. ``He really believed in doing something for the
people that went'' to Vietnam.
   ``You can tell this is from the heart,'' said Glenn Guarino of
Toms Rivers, one of five honor guards from Chapter 200 of the New
Jersey Vietnam Veterans of America. ``You can tell the emotion he
put into the memorial.''
   Added colleague Andrew Marotta, of Brick Township, who broke
down briefly: ``This place will be sacred because our brothers will
be here.''
   Nguyen's $2.5 million design will be financed by a variety of
sources, including veterans' groups, private corporations and the
state, said state Sen. Edward O'Connor, chairman of the memorial
committee.
   Groundbreaking will not take place until most of the money is
raised and construction will take one year, said Tom Moran, visual
arts coordinator for the state Council on the Arts and the
competition's manager.
   Moran said a four-member panel of architects, artists and
designers picked the seven finalists from among more than 400
entries.
   Moran said Nguyen's design ``provides a space for solitude. When
you enter, you must be overcome by a wall of stone that provides
seclusion and private moments away from the outside world.''
   Nguyen said he visited the war memorial in Washington and read
books by Vietnam veterans to get a sense of how they felt about the
war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
