<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     07-04 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says U.S. Should Pay Reparations To Iranians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson urged President Reagan on Monday to
offer reparations to the families of victims of the downed Iranian
airliner, saying an immediate goodwill gesture was needed to save
the lives of American hostages held in Lebanon.
   Jackson called for an investigation and re-evaluation of U.S.
policy in the Persian Gulf. He held a brief news conference at his
Chicago home before departing for Boston for a Fourth of July visit
with Democratic presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson criticized what he called the administration's ``failed
and vague policy'' in the gulf.
   Reagan said the U.S. Navy's shooting down of the Iranian
jetliner with 290 people aboard was ``an understandable accident''
and ordered a full investigation by the Defense Department. The
Pentagon said the airliner was mistaken for an attacking warplane,
and failed to heed warnings.
   But Jackson said the administration was using ``the same
arguments the Russians were making'' after they shot down a Korean
Air Lines jetliner in 1983, killing all 269 people on board.
   ``When the KAL (plane) was shot down, we did not accept those
arguments as being valid, and most people in the world will not
accept our arguments to this point as being valid,'' Jackson said.
   The Democratic presidential candidate said there was ``no
evidence'' that the USS Vincennes was under attack when it shot
down the civilian airliner early Sunday.
   ``I am sincerely concerned that we make a gesture of goodwill
immediately so as to protect the lives of Americans who are in the
region, specifically the Americans who are held hostage there,'' he
said.
   Jackson said the incident complicates the situation in the gulf
at a time when there were indications that forces in Iran favoring
negotiations were gaining strength.
   Reading a prepared statement, Jackson urged Reagan to go on
television to express ``genuine regrets'' about the plane's downing
and ``offer reparations to the families to ease some of the pain.''
   The president has already expressed deep regret over the loss of
life.
   Jackson called for a United Nations force under international
command to keep the gulf waterways open, rather than rely on
unilateral U.S. military actions. However, the navies of several
other nations are also patrolling in the gulf.
   The Reagan administration's policy left U.S. troops ``trapped in
the gulf under these warlike conditions without civilian
oversight,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
