<HEAD>Officials From Non-Aligned Movement Honor Passengers on Jetliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the 101-nation non-aligned
movement observed a minute of silence on Monday to remember the
passengers who were killed when a U.S. Navy ship shot down an
Iranian jetliner.
   The officials are meeting in the capital of Harare to prepare
for a two-day session of the movement's Ministerial Committee on
Economic Cooperation scheduled to open Wednesday.
   The preparatory talks are being chaired by Zimbabwe's permanent
representative to the United Nations, Stan Mudenge, who asked the
officials to stand in silence in memory of those who perished in
the attack.
   Iran, a member of the non-aligned movement, is expected to
attend the ministerial meeting Wednesday.
