<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GreekOrthodoxCongress     07-04 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greek Orthodox Congress,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Orthodox Leader Refers To Success Of Followers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Greek Orthodox Church in the
Western Hemisphere referred Monday to the presidential ambitions of
Gov. Michael Dukakis as an example of Greek-Americans seeking
``loftier goals.''
   Early Greek Orthodox settlers in the United States had to
overcome persecution, Archbishop Iakovos said in his remarks to
nearly 3,500 followers at a biennial conference.
   Today, Iakovos said, the United States is ``a country
resplendent with successful Greek Orthodox believers and citizens.
   ``They (the settlers) see a generation still ascending towards
loftier goals, a Greek-American young man standing at the pinnacle
of an incredible political ascendancy told only in fairy tales.''
   Iakovos commented in delivering the keynote address at the 29th
Clergy-Laity Congress of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of North
and South America.
   The biennial conference comprises workshops and discussions
about church-related issues and policies.
   Iakovos also noted the increasing religious freedom in the
Soviet Union where, he said, ``The pulpit has come out of its sad
silence.''
   The religious leader of some 3 million people from Canada to
Argentina said such examples should foster more faith.
   Before the meeting ends Thursday, it will be addressed by
Dukakis and Vice President George Bush, the likely Republican
presidential nominee.
</TEXT>
