<DOCNO> AP880704-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SaltyRiver     07-04 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salty River,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Agency To Increase Monitoring Of Mississippi River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State environmental officials say they
will monitor the Mississippi River more closely for salt and toxic
substances as the worst drought in years continues to decrease the
freshwater flow.
   ``We're concerned about the toxics going down the river and are
seriously taking a look at it now,'' said Maureen O'Neill, the
Department of Environmental Quality's assistant secretary in charge
of water quality. ``We're not seeing the same dilution factor''
that is normally present.
   So far, levels of toxic substances still are very low, but the
environmental agency will begin taking weekly samples from the
river instead of the monthly tests that are normally taken, O'Neill
said. Public warnings will be issued if toxic levels are found to
be unacceptable, she said.
   The department is getting help in analyzing the samples from the
New Orleans Sewerage and Water Board's laboratory because its own
laboratory is understaffed and backed up with other work, O'Neill
said.
   Meanwhile, communities that get their drinking water from the
lower part of the Mississippi River are seeing chloride
concentrations rise as salt water moves rapidly up the river due to
a lack of freshwater flow.
   At Port Sulphur, drinking water already is nearly double the
federal standard for chlorides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
