<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teachers-RyanWhite     07-04 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers-Ryan White,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ryan White Asks Teachers To Make AIDS ``A Disease, Not a Dirty
Word''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ryan White, the teen-age AIDS patient who
captured national attention with his struggle to attend school,
urged teachers Monday to use education to make his illness ``a
disease, not a dirty word.''
   Looking small for his 16 years but relatively fit except for a
sniffle, White told some 8,000 delegates to the National Education
Association's annual convention that despite his 3{-year struggle
with the disease, ``my life is better now.''
   ``I'm a normal happy teen-ager again. I have a driver's license
and a 1987 Chevy. I attend sports functions and dances. My studies
are important to me. I made the honor role recently, with two As
and two Bs,'' he said.
   ``I have lived 3{ years with AIDS. Now I stand before you to ask
for your help,'' Ryan told the teachers. ``The many people against
me said they weren't against me, but against my disease. Help me
beat the odds and together let's educate and save the children of
the world.''
   ``Teachers can play an important role in helping an AIDS student
be accepted and treated as normal as possible by teaching the
facts, not the myths,'' he said. ``By proper education, AIDS can be
a disease, not a dirty word.''
   The NEA went on record last year in opposition to mandatory or
involuntary AIDS testing of students. Union delegates will vote
later this week on a resolution in support of local policies to
ensure ``free appropriate public education'' for students with AIDS.
   A hemophiliac since birth, Ryan caught AIDS from blood products
he was given to control his disease.
   Ryan's health has improved since last year when he started
taking the drug AZT, which helps prolong the lives of AIDS victims
but doesn't cure them.
   He now attends Hamilton Heights High School in Arcadia, Ind.,
and hopes to graduate in 1991. He told reporters after his address
that he's spending the summer working at a skateboard shop in
Indianapolis and would like to attend the University of Indiana.
   His outlook was far bleaker 3{ years ago when his family lived
in Kokomo, Ind., and he faced taunts and discrimination because of
his illness.
   After he was diagnosed, Kokomo school officials banned him from
classes. After nine months of court battles he won the right to
attend school, only to find more problems.
   ``Because of the lack of education on AIDS, discrimination,
fear, panic and lies surrounded me,'' he said. ``I became the
target of Ryan White jokes, lies about me biting people, spitting
on vegetables and cookies, urinating on bathroom walls. Some
restaurants threw away my dishes. My school locker was vandalized
inside and folders were marked `Fag' and other obscenities.''
   ``I was labeled a troublemaker, my mom an unfit mother, and I
was not welcome anywhere. People would get up and leave so they
would not have to sit anywhere near me. Even at church, people
would not shake my hand,'' he said.
   Last year, his family decided to move 25 miles away to Cicero,
near Arcadia, where school officials used education to create a
welcoming atmosphere for Ryan and his family.
   ``For the first time in three years, we feel we have a home, a
supportive school and lots of friends,'' he said. ``Hamilton
Heights High School is proof that AIDS education in school works.''
</TEXT>
