<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     07-04 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial of Alleged TWA Hijacker Starts Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Shiite Moslem goes on trial
Tuesday for the 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner in which a U.S.
Navy diver was slain, and several of the American passengers say
they're ready to take the stand.
   The trial for Mohammed Hamadi, charged with murder and air
piracy, begins amid high-security in a courtroom at a state prison
in Frankfurt.
   Four armed men hijacked the TWA plane on June 14, 1985, on a
flight from Athens to Rome, and forced it to land in Beirut.
Thirty-nine Americans were held captive for 17 days and U.S. Navy
diver Robert Stethem of Waldorf, Md., was beaten and shot to death.
   Several former U.S. captives aboard the TWA plane have been
asked to testify about the abuse at the hands of their abductors.
Scores have given depositions to West German prosecutors.
   ``I'm ready to go (to the trial),'' said Kurt L. Carlson, a
Chicago-area native who said he was beaten by the hijackers for two
consecutive hours.
   ``I feel strongly about what the hijackers did. All the beating
and the terror _ our lives were threatened every minute on that
plane,'' Carlson told the AP.
   The Frankfurt juvenile court will spend the first part of the
trial looking into the vital question of Hamadi's age, to determine
whether the Lebanese defendant should be tried as a juvenile, young
adult or adult.
   Under West German law, a juvenile is less than age 18, an adult
is age 21 and older, while a young adult is between 18 and 21.
   Hamadi faces a maximum sentence of life imprisonment if the
court convicts him as an adult at the time of the crime. The West
German indictment lists Hamadi's date of birth as June 13, 1964,
but he claims he was born in 1966.
   If he is tried and convicted as a juvenile, the maximum term
would be 15 years. If convicted as an adolescent, the court could
sentence Hamadi either as an adult or a juvenile, depending on how
mature it decides he was at the time of the hijacking.
   Officials say the actual testimony centering on the murder and
air piracy charges is scheduled to begin in September.
   West Germany last year refused a U.S. request to extradite the
hijacker to the United States. Government sources in Bonn told The
Associated Press that concern for the fate of two German hostages
then held in Lebanon influenced their decision.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport on Jan. 13, 1987, after
a search revealed he was carrying liquid explosives.
   His older brother, Abbas Ali Hamadi, was sentenced in April by a
Duesseldorf court to 13 years in prison for kidnapping two West
Germans in Beirut in an attempt to gain freedom for the defendant.
   One of the hostages, Alfred Schmidt, was released in September.
Businessman Rudolf Cordes is still being held in Beirut by the
pro-Iranian Holy Warriors for Freedom Shiite Moslem group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
