<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SharpevilleSix     07-04 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers for Condemned Blacks Seek Permission To Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOEMFONTEIN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for six people
sentenced to hang for the mob killing of a black official filed an
application Monday seeking to appeal a judge's refusal to reopen
the case.
   The five men and a woman, known as the Sharpeville Six, were
convicted of participating in the 1984 killing of a black town
councilor. There has been an international campaign seeking
clemency for the six, and several Western European countries have
threatened to recall their ambassadaors if the hangings take place.
   The six were granted a stay of execution March 17, one day
before they were to hang. In June, a judge extended the stay until
July 19, but rejected a bid to reopen the trial to consider
allegations that police coerced state witnesses.
   Justice Willem Human said only President P.W. Botha could
intervene to save them. Botha has rejected a clemency petition.
   On Monday, defense lawyers filed an application with the chief
justice of the Appellate Court in Bloemfontein seeking permission
to appeal Human's ruling.
   The case has generated controversy in part because the
defendants were not convicted of contributing physically to the
death of Khuzwayo Dlamini.
   They were convicted under the doctrine of common purpose, which
held them responsible because they actively participated in the mob
which killed the councilor in the black township of Sharpeville.
</TEXT>
