<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Espionage     07-04 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Espionage,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish TV Crew Acquitted of Espionage Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGRIGENTO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Monday acquitted five
members of a Spanish TV crew who were accused of espionage for
filming a U.S. Coast Guard facility that was the target of a failed
Libyan missile attack.
   The five were arrested in April 1986 while filming a navigation
station on the tiny Italian island of Lampedusa.
   Earlier that month, Libya had fired two Soviet-made Scud
missiles at the island after U.S. warplanes bombed the Libyan
cities of Tripoli and Benghazi. The missiles fell harmlessly into
the sea.
   The TV crew, four men and one woman, were released hours after
their arrest. Their film was confiscated. They did not attend the
trial.
   State prosecutor Rosario Livatino had requested seven-month
prison terms for the five, but the court issued the acquittals
after just a few minutes of deliberation.
