<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Britain     07-04 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Britain,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Demands More Anti-American Response from Britain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Britain-Airliner in the digest.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American flags were removed from a Heathrow
Airport terminal for U.S. flights on Monday and some British
lawmakers deplored the deadly U.S. missile attack on an Iranian
airliner.
   Iran demanded a stronger anti-American response.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government expressed sorrow
over the attack Sunday on the Iran Air jet that went down with
nearly 300 people aboard, but also said it understood the U.S.
Navy's reason for shooting at the plane.
   Iran's top diplomat in London, charge d'affaires Mohammed Basti,
hinted that the attack might endanger the lives of 18 Western
hostages believed held by pro-Iranian extremists in Lebanon.
   The family of one of the British hostages, Anglican envoy Terry
Waite, appealed to Iran not to retaliate against the captives.
   In recent months, Britain and Iran have been trying to improve
their badly strained relations, raising hopes of freedom for three
Britons missing in Lebanon.
   At Heathrow Airport, police armed with submachine guns patrolled
the terminals. Baggage loaded onto American airlines came under
close scrutiny because of fears of Iranian reprisals.
   Authorities removed American flags put up in honor of the Fourth
of July in a terminal that services most U.S. flights. An airport
statement said it was ``a mark of respect'' for those who died.
   Mrs. Thatcher's government issued a statement Sunday night
saying it ``profoundly'' regretted the disaster but backed the U.S.
Navy's right to defend itself.
   Navy officials said the Airbus 300 was mistaken for an Iranian
F-14 fighter jet as it flew toward the USS Vincennes during a
U.S.-Iranian skirmish in the Persian Gulf. All aboard the plane
were presumed killed.
   Basti said he relayed Iran's ``dismay with the statement'' in a
one-hour visit Monday to the Foreign Office, and said it compared
unfavorably with the responses of other Western countries.
   Britain should ``immediately make a condemnation of this
barbaric act'' and show that British statements ``are not only
based on a special political relationship,'' Basti told reporters
outside the Foreign Office.
   Asked whether the foreign hostages, nine of them Americans, were
now in greater jeopardy, Basti replied: ``It is a natural human
reaction. ... People in the area, they have seen this thing with
their own eyes. ... Naturally they do not remain indifferent.''
   Asked earlier at a news conference how Iran would respond to the
disaster, Basti said: ``I do not disclose what kind of response,
but naturally I prefer a measured response to the magnitude of the
crime.''
   Several legislators from the governing Conservative Party and
the opposition deplored the attack.
   Conservative lawmaker Robert Adley called the Americans
``trigger-happy,'' saying: ``They are burdened with this massive
firepower but they still have not learned the lessons of the
Vietnam War.''
   Labor's Tom Clarke, who last month visited Iran with an
unofficial British delegation on a fence-mending expedition,
complained that Mrs. Thatcher ``might have distanced herself just a
bit more than she did from the American action.''
   Clarke told British Broadcasting Corp. TV that the U.S. response
``to what appears to have been a colossal mistake ... really should
have been much more apologetic than it was.''
   Waite's brother, John, urged Iran not to retaliate against the
hostages.
   ``Two wrongs do not make a right,'' he said.
   ``I think the British nation is horrified by this appalling
tragedy and I want to get (that) over to the Iranians ... so that
they don't feel isolated at least in their grief from the feelings
that all civilized people have,'' John Waite said in a BBC
interview.
   Terry Waite disappeared in Beirut in January 1987 while trying
to win the release of Western hostages.
   The longest-held of the hostages is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped in
Beirut on March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
