<DOCNO> AP880704-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 1736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Wright     07-04 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Wright,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Speaker Says Mistakes Were Made But Iran Also Responsible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright said Monday that
while mistakes were made in the U.S. Navy's downing of an Iranian
civilian aircraft with nearly 300 people aboard, Iran bears some
responsibility for the incident.
   The leader of the Democratic-controlled House also said that the
issue warrants discussion in Congress, but that he accepted the
administration's statements that the jetliner's downing in the
Persian Gulf was a regrettable mistake.
   ``This is an awkward and uncomfortable situation for Americans
to be in,'' the Texas Democrat told reporters at a hastily arranged
news conference during a long-planned five-day trip to London.
   ``It was certainly never our intention in any instance to bring
death to the gulf,'' Wright said. ``It was a great tragedy,
obviously mistakes were made. Nobody's trying to minimize that and
I don't believe the administration seeks to minimize that.''
   However, Wright said, the ``Iranians do bear some responsibility.
   ``I think their government must realize that it places its
civilians in jeopardy when it engages in military attacks on the
sea at the very time a civilian aircraft is scheduled to fly over
the sea.''
   U.S. officials said the commander of the cruiser USS Vincennes
ordered the attack on the airliner on Sunday after the plane, which
he believed was an F-14 military jet, ignored warnings while flying
in a combat zone. All aboard are presumed dead.
   Wright, who earlier met separately with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe, refused to say
whether he wanted to see congressional debate on the incident but
said he expected ``discussion on the issue. It warrants it.''
   But he said it was more important to ``close ranks,'' and
defended the U.S. commander involved, Capt. Will C. Rogers.
   ``(He) was responsible for the lives of the men on his ship,
(and) he must have been mindful of the ... Stark incident,'' when
an Iraqi plane fired on the frigate the USS Stark, killing 37 men
in May 1987.
   Washington accepted Iraq's apology and explanation that it had
mistaken the Stark for an Iranian warship.
   Asked if President Reagan's statements of regret had not been
sufficient, as some British newspapers and politicians have said,
Wright replied: ``I take his expressions of deep and sincere regret
at the loss of human lives at face value. I don't know what more
you expect him to do.''
   Wright said Mrs. Thatcher was ``very supportive and completely
understanding of our anguish'' during their 40-minute meeting.
   He and an official from Mrs. Thatcher's office, who was not
identified according to British custom, said the issue was touched
on briefly during their talks of bilateral relations, the U.S.
trade bill and other topics.
   A Foreign Office official, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Howe and Wright spoke briefly on the subject of the
airliner during their 40-minute meeting. He said they talked mostly
of Northern Ireland and U.S. politics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
