<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Airliner-UnansweredQuestions 2ndLd-Writethru a0648 07-04
1016</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Unanswered Questions, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0648,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian, U.S. Versions of Plane Shoot-Down Differ</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 16th graf pvs, bgng: But Mahallati, with
reports on civilian air schedules being checked; INSERTS 1 graf
after 28th graf pvs, But the United, with report of private
messages sent to Iran</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. and Iranian versions of the downing
of Iran Air Flight 655 differ on at least three major points,
including whether the jetliner was warned and whether it was
outside a commercial air corridor.
   The two nations also contradicted each other on whether the Navy
cruiser Vincennes knew the plane was a commercial airliner, with
the United States saying no and the Iranians saying yes.
   In addition to those points, there are a number of unanswered
questions in the wake of Sunday's missile attack on the Iranian
Airbus in the Strait of Hormuz, which Iran said killed 290 persons.
   At a news conference Sunday confirming that the United States
had shot down the plane, Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the Vincennes sent seven warnings to
the Airbus, three on civilian radio channels and four on military
channels. None were answered, he said.
   Mohammad Ja-Afar Mahallati, Iran's ambassador to the United
Nations, said Monday that ``we definitely reject that there has
been any warning and this case could be verified by international,
independent investigation.''
   Mahallati's comments were made on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America.''
   The U.S. contention was partially supported by the Italian navy,
which was escorting an Italian cargo ship through the strait at the
time.
   The Italian naval vessel Espero heard the Vincennes send four
radio warnings to the pilot of the Iranian plane, but there was no
response, according to a navy official in Rome.
   The Italians didn't say if the four broadcasts were the military
warnings referred to by Crowe. Nor did the Italians say if their
radios were monitoring commercial traffic.
   Crowe said the plane was hit by one missile; the Iranians say it
was struck by two.
   The plane's location and height at the time of the attack also
were subjects of disagreement.
   Crowe said the Iranian plane was four or five miles outside the
established air corridor for the heavily traveled region. That
statement was also supported by the Italian naval officials.
   But Mahallati rejected the U.S. argument. ``It was, indeed, in
the recognized corridor,'' he said.
   In addition, U.S. officials said the plane was at 9,000 feet,
but the official Islamic Republic News Agency said the airliner was
at 7,500 feet.
   The third major contradiction is whether the Navy knew what it
was shooting at. Crowe said Navy officials believed the plane was a
U.S.-made F-14 flown by Iran.
   But Mahallati said, ``It was a premeditated attack, it was a
cold-blooded murder.''
   ABC News quoted Pentagon sources Monday as saying the captain
ordered a check of civilian air schedules in the area, but that the
check was not completed at the time the plane was shot down. The
flight left nearly an hour late, the report said.
   President Reagan on Monday described the incident as ``an
understandable accident.'' Asked about Iranian claims, the
president declared, ``Well, I don't go much by what the Iranians
say _ ever.''
   Reagan, returning to the White House from the presidential
retreat at Camp David, Md., said, ``We're talking about an incident
in which a plane on radar was observed coming in the direction of a
ship in combat and the plane began lowering its altitude. And so I
think it was an understandable accident to shoot and think that
they were under attack from that plane.''
   Reagan's statement raised one of the unanswered questions, which
had been first asked Sunday after Crowe's statement that the plane
was descending toward the Vincennes.
   If the plane had just taken off from Bandar Abbas enroute to
Dubai, as Iran claimed, it likely would not have been descending at
the point where it was hit, said a Pentagon source, who declined to
be identified.
   ``I'd wait until the investigation is completed before I flatly
accepted the statement that it was descending,'' cautioned the
source, who had been stationed in the Persian Gulf.
   Another unanswered question is why the Aegis Air Defense System
aboard the Vincennes was unable to distinguish the Airbus from the
much smaller F-14 fighter jet. The Navy repeated has described
Aegis as the world's most sophisticated electronic defense system
that could differentiate among different fighters.
   Also unclear is whether the plane's transponder was working and
if not, why not.
   Transponders, used routinely on all commercial flights,
continuously broadcast identification information about a plane,
according to a spokesman for the International Civil Aviation
Organization. That information includes the name and number of the
flight, along with type of aircraft.
   Another open question is what the United States and Iran will
each do now.
   Reagan noted, ``I've ordered an investigation and I'm going to
wait until I hear the result of the investigation.''
   After the incident, Reagan said ``our sympathy and condolences
go out to the passengers, crew and their families.''
   But the United States has not yet formally apologized to Iran.
The two nations have not had formal diplomatic relations since
1980, when they were broken by the United States. Also unanswered
is whether the United States will pay reparations.
   However, NBC Nightly News reported Monday that the United States
had sent private messages to Iran repeating what it had said
publicly _ that the shooting down of the airliner was a mistake.
The network also said administration lawyers are looking into the
issue of compensation for the families of the victims.
   As for Iran, it has vowed revenge. President Ali Kahmeini said,
``we wish to warn that the American government will have to suffer
the consequences of its recent crime in the Persian Gulf.''
   Earlier, Tehran Radio said ``the criminal United States should
know that blood unlawfully shed in the disaster...will be avenged
in the same blood-spattered sky over the Persian Gulf.''
</TEXT>
