<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JailShootout-Fire     07-04 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Shootout-Fire,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Crashes Into Law Complex, Causing Shootout and Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGEBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 67-year-old man rammed a truck loaded
with ammunition and fuel through gates at the law enforcement
complex here Monday, starting a 20-minute shootout and a major
fire, authorities said.
   Two officers were slightly injured, and the suspect was
hospitalized with gunshot wounds, authorities said.
   The fire seriously damaged the law enforcement complex, which
houses a jail, the sheriff's department and the city police
department.
   Orangeburg County Sheriff C.R. Smith said he couldn't estimate
the losses but, ``It put us out of business.'' Smith said the 140
inmates in the jail were unharmed, but had to be moved elsewhere.
   Smith said Clyde B. Myers of Branchville drove an old Ford farm
truck through the gates of the Orangeburg-Calhoun Law Enforcement
Complex about 9:15 a.m., wearing a bullet-proof vest and steel
helmet.
   Myers was shot six times _ in his right heel, right foot, right
shoulder, right hand, groin and left elbow _ before being subdued.
He also suffered thermal burns to his left hand and back. He was in
fair condition after surgery at Orangeburg-Calhoun Regional
Hospital, a spokeswoman said.
   Smith said Myers would be charged with arson and assault and
battery with intent to kill.
   Smith said he didn't know Myers' motive but recalled that he
once chained himself to a chair at a County Council meeting in 1985
in a protest against county government.
   ``As soon as he drove through the gates, he entered the back
door of the building firing a shotgun,'' Smith said. ``Our officers
returned fire.''
   Myers then went back out to his truck and got some gasoline.
Smith said the truck had two 500-gallon tanks in it, but the
sheriff was unsure how much gas was in the tanks.
   Myers poured gasoline around the gates and set it on fire,
barricading himself between the truck and a wall, the sheriff said.
   A gun battle ensued, with three state Highway Patrol troopers
who happened to be nearby helping an unspecified number of officers.
   Smith said the storage tanks on the truck ignited, and the
building eventually caught fire.
   ``After it burned a few minutes, it got too hot for him,'' Smith
said. ``He attempted to come out... When he did, he stumbled.
That's when our officers rushed him and were able to subdue him.''
   Fire trucks were then able to get to the blaze, but not before
the front office, jail offices and communications room were
virtually destroyed, Smith said. The rest of the building suffered
serious smoke damage.
   City Department of Public Safety Director Gene Brant said all
communications at the law complex were knocked out by the fire.
Phone service was restored later at an emergency operations center.
   Deputy Allen Bright was shot in the forearm and sheriff's
Detective Everette LaFrance was shot in a finger on his right hand,
Smith said. The officers, both from Orangeburg, were treated for
their injuries at a nearby hospital and released.
   Orangeburg is a city of 15,000 people 40 miles south of
Columbia. Branchville, 18 miles further south, is a town of about
1,800.
</TEXT>
