<DOCNO> AP880704-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Protest     07-04 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Protest,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 42 Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said at least 42 protesters were arrested
and three police officers hurt Monday in demonstrations following
the U.S. missile attack that downed an Iranian passenger jet and
killed all 290 people aboard.
   Eleven people were arrested outside the U.S. Consulate and
another 31 protesters were arrested after demonstrators moved
downtown.
   Police said three officers were treated at a hospital for minor
injuries.
   One person was arrested after a cup of red paint was tossed at
the consulate building and splattered a fashionable private club
next door. Protesters said they used paint because they ``didn't
have time to get real blood.''
   Demonstrators smeared themselves with paint, chanted and carried
a black coffin.
   Protests began in the morning with about 50 people in front of
the Ontario legislature.
   Demonstrators originally planned to simply march to the U.S.
Consulate, but by midafternoon, the group swelled to about 150
people as those from anti-nuclear organizations and others joined
in.
   Police said eight people were charged after they lay down in the
street, tying up morning rush-hour traffic.
   U.S. officials said the airliner was attacked Sunday in the
mistaken belief it was an Iranian warplane as it closed on U.S.
Navy ships operating near the Strait of Hormuz in the Persian Gulf
and did not respond to warnings.
</TEXT>
