<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Routes 1stLd-Writethru a0593 07-04 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Routes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Group Announces Inquiry; Two Airlines Change Routes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The International Civil ... with 3 grafs
to UPDATE with Iran filing official request for investigation.
PICKS up 5th graf pvs bgng, In Tokyo, Japan ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Airline Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international airline group urged governments
Monday to cooperate with an inquiry into the U.S. downing of an
Iranian jetliner, and at least two airlines announced route changes
to avoid the area of the incident.
   The International Air Transport Association said the
Montreal-based International Civil Aviation Organization would
conduct a ``full and objective'' investigation into the shooting
down of the Iran Air Airbus 300 by a U.S. Navy ship in the Persian
Gulf on Sunday.
   The airline association deplored ``the use of force against a
civil aircraft and strongly urges all governments to take the
necessary steps to prevent recurrence of such incidents.''
   The International Civil Aviation Organization, a U.N. agency,
said later Monday that Ali Akbar Golruni, Iran's representative to
the organization, filed a formal request for an emergency meeting
of the agency's council to set up an inquiry into the crash.
   But organization president Assad Kotaite said his agency needs
more information, particularly from the United States, before
granting the request.
   ``We have not received ... preliminary reports regarding the
circumstances from the parties involved, except from Iran,''
Kotaite said.
   In Tokyo, Japan Air Lines said its twice-weekly flight from
Tokyo to Athens, Greece, would alter its route over the gulf to
avoid the area where the shooting took place.
   The airline said it will begin flying over Abu Dhabi in the
United Arab Emirates instead of over Dubai, also in the same
country but closer to Iran and the Strait of Hormuz. The Iran Air
plane was flying to Dubai from Iran.
   In Hong Kong, Cathay Pacific Airways said the daily Hong Kong to
London flight also would alter its route over the gulf. Spokeswoman
Rebecca Chan said Hong Kong carrier's planes do not fly over the
area where the Iranian jet was shot down, but the slight route
change to the south will take aircraft even further from the spot.
   A JAL official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a JAL
DC-10 with 156 passengers and 16 crew members left Tokyo for Athens
on Monday using the new route.
   Officials from both companies said the route change will add
about five minutes to the trip.
   The United States said its forces mistook the wide-bodied Iran
Air plane for a F-14 fighter and shot it down when it failed to
heed seven warnings.
   President Reagan said the United States would conduct a full
investigation. Iranian officials have demanded the United Nations
or another independent world body investigate the incident.
</TEXT>
