<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0697 07-04 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0697,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls For End To Iran-Iraq War, Urges Iran to Reconsider
Threats</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, bgng: After the, with
later Jackson comment</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis renewed his call Monday
for an international effort to end the Iran-Iraq war and urged Iran
to reconsider its threats to respond with terrorism to the U.S.
Navy's downing of an Iranian passenger jet.
   ``As long as this senseless war between Iran and Iraq continues
... as long as we and the entire international community fail to
use our combined efforts to stop it, there will be more tragedies,
more heartaches and the ever-present risk of more accidents in the
(Persian) Gulf,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic presidential nominee-to-be hosted rival Jesse
Jackson for dinner at his Brookline, Mass., home before the two
candidates and their wives attended the traditional Fourth of July
Boston Pops concert alongside the Charles River.
   Aides billed the evening as a social gathering but said Dukakis'
search for a running mate was likely to come up in discussion.
Jackson skirted questions about likely dinner-table conversation on
his arrival at Boston's Logan Airport.
   ``It's a private meeting. He's the host and we are the guests,''
he told reporters.
   Arriving at Dukakis' home, where he was greeted by a crowd of
about 200 onlookers, Jackson was asked if the subject of a running
mate would be discussed.
   ``Dinner, dinner, dinner,'' he replied.
   The Massachusetts governor has said Jackson is being considered
for the No. 2 spot on the ticket, but it is viewed as highly
unlikely that Dukakis would offer it to him.
   After the dinner, Dukakis emerged and told reporters, ``We were
talking about lots of things.''
   Jackson said then he had no comment. Later, arriving at his
Boston hotel, he told reporters: ``Our conversation is private, and
should remain private.''
   At a morning appearance at the USS Constitution, the Navy's
oldest commissioned warship, Dukakis departed from the text of his
speech Monday to demand an end to the nearly 8-year-old gulf war.
   ``I believe that the United States must take the lead ... to
stop this war permanently,'' Dukakis said.
   ``And while we all deeply regret the tragedy, this is no time
for acts of terror or revenge in response to the incident. So I
urge the government of Iran to reconsider its threats and to join
us and the entire international community in ending a war that
already has taken the lives of more than one million people,'' he
said.
   The USS Vincennes downed the Iran Air Airbus Sunday during
fighting with Iranian gunboats, presumably killing all 290 people
aboard the commercial jet. The Pentagon reported that the Vincennes
crew believed the wide-bodied Airbus was an F-14 fighter about to
attack the ship.
   Iran vowed to avenge the ``premeditated, cold-blooded murder''
and Iranian President Ali Khamenei said Monday that Iran is ``ready
to fight ... American aggression.''
   Dukakis said the United States clearly has the right ``to defend
our forces against imminent threats, and apparently the shooting
down of the airliner occurred over what appears to have been an
unprovoked attack against our forces.''
   Dukakis' speech to a small gathering at the Charlestown Navy
Yard was a variation on his standard stump talk, peppered with
references to his immigrant past, central campaign theme of
economic opportunity and attacks on the Reagan administration.
   ``Respect for the Constitution and for the rule of law is the
most basic, the most conservative, the most important principle of
our democratic society,'' Dukakis said. ``And it must begin at the
top _ in the White House, in the Defense Department, and in the
office of the attorney general of the United States.''
   He also paid tribute to the colonists who fought the
Revolutionary War for American independence.
   ``Ours was not just a revolution against one government,''
Dukakis said in his holiday speech. ``It was a revolution of the
human spirit. And it lives wherever men and women are taking into
their own hands the responsibility to build a better world.''
   The Dukakis campaign said the menu for the dinner with Jackson
was standard New England fare: homemade clam chowder, fish and
vegetables, and chocolate cake for dessert.
</TEXT>
