<FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-88 2252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Teachers 2ndLd-Writethru a0643 07-04 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0643,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEA Head Urges Creation of ``Learning Laboratories'' In Each State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds final graf with results of AFT elections.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest teachers union endorsed
overwhelmingly Monday a proposal that each state name name at least
one school district a ``learning laboratory'' where teachers could
experiment and take the lead in improving schools.
   ``Hot dog! You did it!'' said Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of
the National Education Association, after the delegates gathered
for their annual convention passed her pet proposal by voice vote.
   Futrell called the idea ``our most ambitious reform effort to
date.''
   In a 45-minute keynote address before 8,227 delegates gathered
for the NEA's annual convention, Futrell had urged teachers to
establish ``a national network of innovative school districts.''
   Such districts, she said, might do away with academic tracking,
finance schools by means other than property taxes, experiment with
more flexible scheduling, or anything else it wanted to try in the
name of reform.
   In San Francisco, 3,000 teachers gathered for the rival American
Federation of Teachers annual convention adopted a similar program
of school experimentation. The AFT plan called for establishment of
thousands of ``schools within schools'' where groups of six or more
teachers could try innovative educational ideas free of
bureaucratic meddling.
   AFT delegates heard Monday from Pulitzer Prize-winning
sociologist Paul Starr, who warned that education vouchers that
would allow parents to choose between public or private schools at
taxpayer expense are ``a recipe for inflation'' that would destroy
public education.
   ``In many ways, the educational voucher proposals resemble third
party payments in health care ... Vouchers would encourage private
schools in part to keep themselves exclusive,'' he said. ``Third
party payment is a recipe for inflation in any sector. To introduce
it into education would be fiscally reckless.''
   Starr, an authority on the economics of medical care, said
vouchers were ``an illusory tonic that would make the whole
educational system ... far more stratified'' and ethnically
fragmented.
   Teachers generally applauded the NEA ``learning laboratories''
initiative but some expressed mixed feelings.
   ``I'm a little afraid that it may be just another experiment. It
could be limited to districts that are already innovating,'' said
Kathleen Conklin, who teaches English at Malcolm X Shabazz High
School in Madison, Wis.
   Chester Finn, assistant U.S. Secretary of Education for research
and improvement, called the AFT and NEA reform programs ``10
percent good, 90 percent bad.''
   ``That they are willing to admit that things aren't hunky-dory
in schools, that much is good,'' he said in a telephone interview.
``But the bad part is that they seem to suggest that we need to
have a vast experiment, as if we didn't know or have the faintest
idea of what works in schools.''
   ``The reason these things don't happen is because the teacher
unions won't let them happen,'' he said.
   Both Futrell and AFT president Albert Shanker have said
repeatedly that the real enemies of reform are the Reagan
administration which has failed to support schools with leadership
and funds, and states which have mandated educational change from
on high without teacher input.
   Presidential politics was the second major theme in Futrell's
address. Last week, the NEA board backed Michael Dukakis for the
Democratic nomination, and Futrell heaped praise on him as someone
who ``understands and embodies the link between education and the
American dream.''
   The nation needs ``a president who will give us a fair deal
instead of an arms deal, a drug deal, or an insider deal,'' she
said, ``a president who will invest more to make every American
child a star than he will to fill God's heaven with star wars.''
   Neither teacher union plans to make a final presidential
endorsement until after the major party conventions this summer.
   The AFT delegates Monday night re-elected Shanker, 59, who was
unopposed for his eighth two-year term as president of the
677,000-member union. The delegates also re-elected longtime AFT
secretary-treasurer Robert G. Porter and filled 38 vice presidents'
posts, including four new ones.
  
</TEXT>
