<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Japan-Markets     07-04 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Monday, while stock prices fell slightly.
   The dollar finished at 134.85 yen, up 0.35 yen from last
Friday's close. It started the week at 135.15 yen and ranged
between 134.60 yen and 135.20 yen during the day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main barometer, fell 2.13 points, or 0.077 percnt, to close at
27,360.39 points.
   ``The dollar was bought in early trading because of the Middle
East situation,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial
bank in Tokyo. The U.S. Navy shot down an Iranian jetliner over the
Persian Gulf Sunday.
   But the dollar eased off mainly on profit-taking and
anticipation of the Fourth of July holiday in the United States,
and also partly because of market caution about possible Bank of
Japan intervention, another dealer said.
   Traders said the central bank did not intervene on behalf of the
yen, but news reports over the weekend said the bank has plans to
stem the dollar's climb if the currency's rise quickens.
   On the stock exchange, ``the trend continues from Saturday,''
said one trader. He said the market is likely continue on its
present course as long as the dollar and interest rates continue on
theirs.
   ``You're not going to get any real buying until you see
stability in currency and bond markets,'' he said.
   ``The problem with that is that the longer they wait, the more
difficult it becomes,'' he said. ``The foreign exchange market has
built up considerable momentum.''
</TEXT>
