<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ford-Ambulances 1stLd-Writethru   07-04 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford-Ambulances, 1st Ld-Writethru,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer, Fire Chiefs Groups Urge Action On Ford Van, Ambulance
Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS year to 1983 in graf 4 bgng ``Last year;'' also
moving general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizations of consumers and fire chiefs have
asked the federal government to act on what they call an imminent
fire hazard in 210,000 Ford vans and ambulances caused by
inadequate repairs.
   The Center for Auto Safety and the International Association of
Fire Chiefs released statements Sunday saying the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration has neglected the problems. They sent
separate letters Friday to Transportation Secretary James Burnley.
   Last year, in response to reports of fuel-system problems that
caused fires, Ford recalled 193,000 1983-87 E-250 and E-350 model
Econoline vans and 16,000 1983-87 ambulances built on the E-350
Econoline chassis.
   Ford spokesman Chuck Snearly said the automaker believes the
modifications performed under the recalls ``are doing the job they
were intended to do and we are making every effort to complete
these recalls as quickly as possible.''
   But the Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based group often
at odds with the auto industry and its regulators, petitioned NHTSA
on May 10 to order a new recall of the ambulances because of
improperly installed hoses that may have caused coolant to leak and
set fire to engines.
   ``We have concerns that the NHTSA has not responded to our May
10 defect petition, and at the same time, fires on Ford ambulances
are occurring better than one per week across the country,'' CAS
spokesman Robert Dewey said from Washington, D.C.
   Fewer than 10 percent of the Ford vans were repaired within
seven months of the initial recall, and 21 Ford ambulances,
including three that were repaired under the recall, have caught
fire since March 24, Dewey said.
   Warren E. Isman, president of the fire chiefs' group, criticized
the ``lack of assertive action'' by NHTSA.
   ``Since fire and emergency services provide over 60 percent of
the pre-hospital emergency medical care in this country, we are in
double jeopardy because we also respond to the vehicle fires,''
Isman said in the letter to Brimley.
   ``It is difficult to fully protect the public when emergency
response personnel themselves are not safe,'' Isman said.
   On June 24, the American Ambulance Association, a
Washington-based organization representing private ambulance
operators, told NHTSA Ford may have done an inadequate job of
repairing the ambulances and called for a federal investigation.
   Clarence Ditlow of the Center for Auto Safety said earlier
recalls to fix problems were ``two little, too late.''
   ``Ford ambulances and vans continue to catch fire and burn
because the recall repairs are inadequate or not done at all,''
Ditlow said in a statement. ``While Americans burn in Ford fires,
the NHTSA has done little.''
</TEXT>
