<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Dollar-Gold     07-04 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: This stands for AM-Dollar-Gold</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar jumped on Monday on news that the
U.S. Navy shot down an Iranian passenger jet with 290 people on
board.
   But gold, after a brief spurt, ended little changed in dull
European trading.
   The dollar's upward trend against all the major currencies
followed a sharp rise on Asian markets, where the business day ends
before Europe's begins.
   The dollar often rises during periods of international tensions
because it is regarded as a safe haven for investment.
   The Deutsche Bundesbank, Germany's central bank, continued to
intervene in foreign exchange markets to halt the dollar's climb,
but traders said it had little effect.
   ``The Bundesbank was selling dollars, but with markets in the
U.S. closed for a holiday, there weren't any real trends, and sheer
momentum carried the dollar up,'' said one trader in Frankfurt.
   Dealers in London cautioned that Monday was a ``false market,''
because American banks and businesses were closed for the Fourth of
July holiday.
   In Tokyo the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 134.85 after
profit-taking. Later, in London, it was quoted at 135.40 yen.
   The British pound continued to fall in London, despite the Bank
of England's decision to signal a half-point increase in the the
British commercial banks' base lending rate to 10 percent, its
second hike in less than a week. One pound cost $1.6825 Monday,
cheaper than late Friday's $1.7023.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
1.8295 West German marks, up from 1.8213; 1.5233 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5130; 6.1595 French francs, up from 6.1375; 2.0575 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0530; 1,353.25 Italian lire, up from 1,352.50,
and 1.2215 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2190.
   The absence of U.S. traders on Monday kept European gold trading
limited, dealers in Zurich said, although the downing of the
Iranian jetliner initially boosted the price of gold. But lack of
follow-through buying in Europe pressured the metal back downward,
they said.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $437.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $437. In Zurich, the bid price was
$437.50, unchanged from late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.24 to close at a bid $439.64.
   Silver was quoted in London late Monday at a bid price of $6.73
a troy ounce, down from Friday's $6.74.
</TEXT>
