<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Koppers     07-04 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Arranging Sale of Koppers Unit, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beazer PLC is expected to announce the sale of
Koppers Co.'s chemical unit to a group of managers in a leveraged
buyout valued at $550 million to $650 million, a report published
Monday said.
   Beazer, the British construction firm that agreed to acquire
Koppers last month for $1.81 billion, is expected to announce a
preliminary agreement by Tuesday, according to The New York Times.
   Brian Beazer, who heads the company, announced before the merger
agreement was signed that he intended to sell Koppers' chemical and
allied products division. The Times said the division accounted for
about 40 percent of the Pittsburgh-based company's $1.5 billion in
revenue last year.
   Under terms of the merger agreement, Beazer granted Koppers
management 45 days to draw up a buyout plan before he offered the
unit to other potential purchasers. That period was then extended
until Aug. 5.
   In a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy a company
and then pay off debt with the target company's cash flow or the
sale of its assets.
   Sterling Group, a Houston-based investment bank run by Gordon A.
Cain, will provide financing for the buyout, the paper said.
   Cain, according to the Times, has played a major role in recent
years in reviving troubled companies in the refining and chemical
industries. In April, Cain sold Cain Chemical Co. to Occidental
Petroleum Corp. for $1.25 billion in cash and the assumption of $1
billion in debt.
   The Times said the involvement of Cain is likely to give the
deal considerable credibility in the chemical industry.
</TEXT>
